<FILEID>AP-NR-12-10-88 0016EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SupperClubFire     12-10 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Supper Club Fire,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judges Orders Hearings on Beverly Hills Fire Claims Cases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFORT, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state appeals court has ordered hearings
on damage claims against the state in the Beverly Hills Supper Club
fire that killed 165 people in 1977.
   The Kentucky Board of Claims had summarily dismissed a group of
claims filed against the state by the estates of seven victims of
the fire at the club in Southgate in northern Kentucky.
   The state Court of Appeals said Friday that the board and other
administrative agencies have no statutory authority to dismiss
claims on their own.
   The seven claims were consolidated when the board's action was
appealed to Campbell Circuit Court. The circuit court was upheld by
the 2-1 appellate ruling.
   Saying it had the ``inherent'' power to do so, the board
dismissed the claims without notice in 1987. The board said it would
not have been liable to the claimants, anyway.
   But the appeals court said that administrative agencies, unlike
courts, have no ``inherent'' powers.
   The board was created by the General Assembly to handle damage
claims against state agencies.
   The claims at issue were not filed against a specific state
agency. The Board of Claims suggested the proper agency would be the
Department of Housing, Buildings and Construction, which includes
the state fire marshal's office, the appeals court said.
</TEXT>
