<1ST_LINE>r a PM-YaleProtester     12-10 0476</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yale Protester,0491</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yale Bursar Stages Weekly One-man Protest Against School Abortions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At lunchtime every Friday, it's not
difficult to find Yale University's bursar: He's out picketing the
Ivy League school's health services building in a one-man protest
against Yale abortion policies.
   Francis R. Nicoll, 58, the university's bursar since 1974, began
his weekly picketing in January and has missed only a couple Fridays
since then.
   ``You need to do things regularly that you believe in,'' said
Nicoll, who is also Yale's assistant treasurer. ``That is all that
is needed. You don't have to make a lot of noise.''
   Nicoll, who believes abortions under all circumstances are wrong,
said his protest is aimed at a policy that he said requires
everyone, including students and parents opposed to abortions, to
help pay for the procedures.
   Mandatory health fees, which support the operations of University
Health Services, are included in tuition.
   Nicoll said he was told by a source at the health services
center, which also provides care to university employees, that an
average of four to five abortions are performed a week.
   But Alan West, a health services spokesman, said the figure was
significantly lower and included both students and Yale employees.
Abortions are performed only one morning a week at the center, he
said.
   Nicoll, who is joined by his wife about two Fridays a month,
carries the same large picket at each of his protests. It reads:
``Yale Brutally Murders Unborn Children Here Each Week.''
   Nicoll, a 1952 Yale graduate and founder of a group called Yale
for Life, also hands out literature.
   About one-third of the students who enter the building accept his
literature, he said. The rest either ignore him or tell him they
oppose his position.
   ``I don't know of any students seeking an abortion who, because
of Frank Nicoll, say, `I am going to keep the baby and give it up
for adoption,''' West said. ``I think the students are generally on
the liberal side, enough so that they think it's a pesonal
decision.''
   Nicoll said administration officials have not tried to discourage
him from protesting.
   ``On the contrary, they ordinarily say, `You're wrong, we don't
agree with you' or `Way to go,' but they always say , `It's great
you have the freedom to say what you want,''' the bursar said.
   As bursar, Nicoll is responsible for collecting all tuition,
room, board and miscellaneous charges, as well as all student loan
payments.
   He has participated in several anti-abortion marches in
Washington, but said he didn't learn until last fall that abortions
were being performed at the health services center.
   Abortions have been performed at health service since the late
1970s or early 1980s, West said.
   Nicoll said he will continue his weekly protest until Yale
changes its policy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
