<1ST_LINE>r w BC-NPCElection     12-10 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-NPC Election,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>National Press Club Elects Officers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peter Holmes, an assistant managing editor of
The Washington Times, was elected Friday night as the 1989 president
of the National Press Club.
   Holmes defeated Douglas Turner, Washigton bureau chief for the
Buffalo News, by a vote of 334-148 in balloting that attracted one
of the largest turnouts in the club's history.
   NPC Election Committee Chairman Frank Aukofer reported the final
results of the election, which also decided other Press Club
officers and its board of governors.
   In addition to Holmes, other winners of the balloting were:
   Vice President, Judy Grande, Washington correspondent, Cleveland
Plain Dealer. She was unopposed.
   Secretary, Mick Rood, Reporter, States News Service
   Treasurer, Tom Squitieri, Reporter, Boston Herald
   Financial Secretary, Vera Glaser, Editor, Washingtonian magazine.
   Rood defeated Ed Schaefer, a reporter for the Richmond (Ohio)
Daily News, by a vote of 263-221; Squitieri, a reporter for the
Boston Herald who lost a bid for the club's presidency last year,
defeated Jessie Stearns, who runs an independent news service
serving several Kansas newspapers, by a vote of 349-136; and Glaser
defeated syndicated columnist Ralph de Toledano by a vote of 383-103.
   Three people reelected to the club's board were: Kathryn Kahler,
a correspondent for the Newhouse newspaper group; Greg Spears, a
reporter with the Knight-Ridder newspapers and Dennis Melaned, a
correspondent covering defense and energy for McGraw-Hill World News.
   Founded in 1908, the NPC membership includes about 5,000 working
and retired journalists, journalism professors and public relations
professionals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
