<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Names     12-10 0924</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Names,0964</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HACKENSACK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Morton Downey Jr., the ultraconservative
talk show host known for intimidating and haranguing his guests, has
filed for divorce, charging his wife of 10 years with ``extreme
cruelty.''
   Downey's divorce suit said Kim Cotton Downey's moodiness and
jealousy led her to create public disturbances and embarrass her
husband.
   The couple, married in 1978, have separated since Nov. 1 and have
had no communication for the last several months, said the lawsuit
filed Dec. 1 in Superior Court.
   The action proposes equitable distribution of all property
acquired by the couple during their marriage.
   The lawsuit cites several incidents, including one in 1980 in
Washington, in which she allegedly locked her husband out of their
hotel room, and another in a Princeton restaurant this year in which
she allegedly shouted at him loudly enough for all patrons to hear.
   Mrs. Downey has an unlisted telephone number and could not be
reached for comment. Downey, 55, would not comment on the matter,
said his assistant, Missy Tshudy.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Humorist Erma Bombeck, whose last five books have
sold more more than 15 million copies, has signed a three-book
contract with a new publisher, Harper & Row.
   The terms of the contract were not disclosed, but there were
estimates that it was for nearly $12 million.
   ``All I'll say is, it's a good estimate,'' Ms. Bombeck said
Friday. The syndicated newspaper columnist's previous books were
published by McGraw-Hill.
   ``McGraw-Hill is selling off its general book division, so it
wasn't unusual for us to approach another publisher,'' said Bombeck,
61.
   The first of her new books is for children recovering from
cancer, she said. Harper & Row will donate 100,000 copies of the
book _ titled ``I Want to Grow Hair, I Want to Grow Up, I Want to Go
to Boise'' _ to children who want them, Ms. Bombeck said.
   The second book, about family vacations, is scheduled for
publication in the fall of 1990. The topic and publication date of
the third book are not settled, the writer said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leslie Nielsen, whose film ``The Naked Gun:
From the Files of Police Squad'' set post-Thanksgiving box office
records, has been honored with a star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame.
   His star, the 1,884th on the Walk, was unveiled Friday by Johnny
Grant, chairman of the Walk Committee and honorary mayor of
Hollywood, and Bill Welsh, president of the sponsoring Hollywood
Chamber of Commerce.
   Nielsen, 66, stars as the hard-boiled detective Lt. Frank Drebin,
who stumbles on a murder plot in Paramount Pictures' movie adapted
from the 1982 ``Police Squad'' television series. The movie earned a
record $9.3 million its first weekend out.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American television star Bronson Pinchott bought a
rare, 500-year-old manuscript of French plays from Sotheby's with a
winning bid that was six times the top estimate, officials at the
auction house said.
   Pinchott, who lives in Hollywood, paid $218,000 for the book of
miracle plays at an auction of Western manuscripts here Tuesday.
   ``It would have great appeal to someone who spends his whole life
confronting performing scripts,'' said Sotheby's expert, Christopher
de Hamel. The book's value was estimated at just one-sixth the top
bid.
   Pinchott, 29, stars in the ABC comedy ``Perfect Strangers'' as
Balki Bartokomous, a Mediterranean immigrant. The New York-born
actor also appeared in the films ``Risky Business'' and ``Beverly
Hills Cop.''
   Miracle plays dramatizing the lives of saints and miracles were
popular in the Middle Ages and are the foundation of modern
performing arts.
   The manuscript was written in the early 15th century in French
rhyming verse with stage directions in Latin. Each play opens with
the actors blowing trumpets and an angel calling for silence.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dolores Ibarruri, the Spanish Communist
leader who became known as the legendary ``La Pasionaria'' because
of her fiery speeches during the Spanish Civil War, quietly
celebrated her 93rd birthday.
   Ibarruri received flowers, telegrams and phone calls Friday, as
well as visits from Soviet, Bulgarian and Romanian diplomats, said
Irene Falcon, her longtime secretary and friend.
   Ibarruri spent the day at home with her daughter, Amaya, and her
granddaughter, Dolores, Falcon said.
   Ibarruri, a founder of the Spanish Communist Party in 1920 and
now the party's figurehead president, won fame during the 1936-39
war for inflammatory radio broadcasts exhorting Republican forces to
defeat Francisco Franco's fascist army.
   The Republicans lost, and Franco took power.
   Ibarruri, who spent 38 years in exile in the Soviet Union,
returned to the Spanish capital in 1977 following Franco's death two
years earlier.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actors F. Murray Abraham, George Hearn, Mariel
Hemingway and Christopher Reeve paid tribute to their immigrant
heritage in a ceremony at Ellis Island.
   ``Nearly 17 million immigrants passed through these halls: the
parents or grandparents of almost half of the Americans alive
today,'' said Hearn, known for his role in Broadway's ``Sweeney
Todd.''
   The performers, led by Hearn, read a statement Friday asking
other Americans to remember their immigrant ancestry and to turn
dreams of a better world into reality.
   Abraham enrolled six family members on the American Immigrant
Wall of Honor, a permanent exhibit where Americans can have
ancestors' names inscribed for a $100 donation. The ceremony was
aimed at drawing attention to the wall, which will stop accepting
names in February.
   The island is closed for a $140 million restoration project and
the creation next year of The Ellis Island Immigration Museum.
</TEXT>
