<FILEID>AP-NR-12-10-88 0136EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Thailand     12-10 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Thailand,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Student Killed, Seven Others Wounded In Charity Concert</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One youth was shot dead and seven others
were wounded when rival groups of vocational school students clashed
at an outdoor charity concert, police said today.
   The violence occurred Friday as one of Thailand's most popular
rock bands, Carabao, entertained a crowd of 100,000 at Royal Field
near the walls of Bangkok's Grand Palace to raise funds for victims
of the recent floods and landslides in southern Thailand.
   Police Lt. Winai Rungrugskul said 60 students who were taken into
custody and later released were fined 20 baht (78 cents) each for
possessing knives and clubs.
   Police arrested one vocational student who they said was carrying
a pistol and a plastic bomb. Two homemade bombs exploded at the
concert but no one was injured.
   The Nation English-language newspaper quoted Metropolitan Police
Commissioner Lt. Gen. Manas Krutchaiyant as saying security forces
were outnumbered by the youths and unable to control the crowd.
   ``We were lucky that the explosions were drowned by the music and
most of the concert-goers were not aware of what was happening ...
otherwise there would have been a stampede, '' the paper quoted him
as saying.
   Vocational school students in Thailand have a history of violent
rivalries that have occasionally resulted in deaths.
</TEXT>
