<DOCNO> AP881210-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-10-88 0138EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Dance     12-10 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dance,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Opus McShann' by Alvin Ailey Is Premiered</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alvin Ailey turns up the heat and speeds the
blood pressure with ``Opus McShann,'' his new dance created to
recordings made by blues and boogie woogie pianist Jay McShann, now
72.
   ``Opus McShann'' is one of Ailey's ``show biz'' dances, which
critics complain about when there are several in a row but miss when
there are none for awhile. ``Opus McShann'' has less glitz and more
effectiveness than some in that category. The New York premiere on
Friday evoked scenes from Kansas City, McShann's headquarters for
much of his career.
   A man in purple tails beckoned the company onto the City Center
stage. They're all dressed up for dancing and strike a fashion-show
pose before cutting loose with some limber-limbed, down-and-dirty
jazz dancing. The woman in the most elegant formal gown will later
prove to be a stripper.
   Carl Bailey and Gary DeLoatch are hilarious as the last drunks
left under a swaying string of lights after a dance. They may be
drunk but they manage some fancy, unison footwork. McShann plays
``Doo Wah Doo'' and sings in his nasal blues style, ``Who's gonna
carry me home? I can't leave that gal alone.''
   Eleven dancers, probably in the bar of a sporting house, dance
``Confessin' the Blues.'' Sharrell Mesh-Alexander dances for an
indifferent Andre Tyson while McShann embellishes and improvises
``Gee Baby Ain't I Good to You?'' into an instrumental anthem.
Finally Tyson wakes up to the sexiness being displayed around him
and pulls Miss Mesh-Alexander, now seated, and her chair into the
wings.
   Marilyn Banks, Desmond Richardson, David St. Charles and Stephen
Smith were outstandingly lithe and snake-hipped to ``I Ain't Mad at
You.''
   A group lindy hop to ``Jumpin' the Blues,'' choreographed by
Swing Society veterans Frank Manning and Norma Miller, was broken up
by four members of the Ku Klux Klan.
   Dudley Williams did a solo ``How Long?'' which became a
meditation on anti-black activities. During it, the four Klansmen
melted away. It was obvious that Ailey was just mentioning this, not
doing a deep enough study of it to dent the rollicking good-time
mood of ``Opus McShann.''
   The blues can be a very ebullient music and Ailey has created a
joyous dance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
