<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NATO     12-10 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NATO,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NATO Determined To Continue Policy Of Adequate Force Size, Arms
Control</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT J. WIELAARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NATO remains determined to continue a
policy it believes has succeeded so far: maintaining adequate
military forces while seeking cuts in conventional and nuclear
forces with the East.
   The foreign ministers of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization,
ending a two-day meeting Friday, said they welcomed the unilateral
offer by Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev to cut Soviet forces
by 500,000 troops, or nearly 10 percent, over the next two years.
   ``Promising prospects are opening up for an improved East-West
dialogue,'' they said in a statement.
   But Secretary of State George P. Shultz and other delegates said
the West should not overreact to Gorbachev's decision to withdraw
50,000 troops and 5,000 tanks from Eastern Europe, notably East
Germany, Czechoslovakia and Hungary.
   ``Being encouraged doesn't mean that you just go bananas and
forget about what got you here and so you want to keep doing the
things that are constructive,'' Shultz told reporters.
   He said that after the Soviet troop cuts, the Warsaw Pact still
will have an enormous advantage in battle tanks, artillery and other
armaments.
   The cuts ``will be significant and make a difference,'' Shultz
said. ``But they leave a situation still very assymmetrical.''
   He said the Warsaw Pact's edge in divisions would be reduced to
2.91-to-1 from 2.99, in tanks to 2.18-to-1 from 2.76, and in
artillery to 1.74-to-1 from 2.30.
   NATO Secretary General Manfred Woerner said, ``We look upon Mr.
Gorbachev with sympathy and encourage his reform efforts.''
   But he said NATO must keep its defenses strong and modernize
weapons even while negotiating cutbacks in conventional forces in
Europe with the Warsaw Pact in talks expected to open next month in
Vienna, Austria.
   Soviet forces in Europe, which NATO estimates at 2.2 million,
``still exceed any reasonable defense need,'' the foreign ministers
said in their statement.
   On Thursday, the Western allies gave a broad outline of NATO's
negotiating position at the Conventional Stability Talks with the
Warsaw Pact.
   The talks are to begin once a 35-nation human rights conference
in Vienna ends.
   The allies said they want to reduce the total number of tanks in
the area between the Atlantic Ocean and the Ural Mountains to
40,000, leaving East and West each with 20,000.
   Under the NATO proposal, the Soviet Union could keep a maximum of
12,000 tanks on the soil of its East European allies, down from
37,000 now.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
