<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Angola,0155</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S.-Mediated Peace Talks On Angola To Resume Monday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRAZZAVILLE, Congo (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S.-mediated peace talks on Angola,
suspended Dec. 3 when the South African delegation suddenly left,
will resume Monday, diplomatic sources say.
   The aim is for an agreement between South Africa, Angola and Cuba
that will lead to the withdrawal of the estimated 50,000 Cuban
troops from Angola and independence for the territory of South-West
Africa, Angola's southern neighbor.
   After the talks broke off, the Cuban and Angolan delegations
accused South Africa of negotiating in bad faith and charged
Pretoria with foiling a possible peace accord.
   South African Foreign Minister Pik Botha said his delegation had
to go home to consult its government on verification of the Cuban
withdrawal.
   South Africa has tied the Cuban withdrawal to independence for
South-West Africa, also called Namibia, on grounds the Cubans would
be a threat to an independent Namibia.
