<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Winds-Fire 5thLd-Writethru a0747 12-10 1007</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Winds-Fire, 5th Ld - Writethru, a0747,1031</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Santa Ana Winds Fuel Blaze That Hits An Additional 36 Homes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE damage reports, raise disaster
declaration; containment estimate, injury reports; picks up 9th
graf: `The fire raced ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos LA11,LA12</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A blowtorch of dry Santa Ana wind and blazing
embers destroyed 15 expensive homes and damaged 25 others Friday in
a roaring 3,000-acre brush fire that chased residents from their
beds for a third day and prompted the governor to declare a state of
emergency.
   The firestorm, driven by erratic gusts of up to 70 mph blasting
off the desert, hit the northwestern San Fernando Valley. It added
new losses to the 22 homes burned and many others damaged Wednesday
and Thursday, when the wind toppled trucks and knocked out power to
half a million customers.
   Late Friday afternoon, Gov. George Deukmejian issued a terse
order declaring a state of emergency in Los Angeles County. The
order makes people eligible to apply for aid under some state
programs and is a first step toward seeking federal aid.
   By nightfall Friday, the winds had eased somewhat, and most of
the thousands who had fled returned to their homes. During the day,
schools were closed and evacuation centers were set up at campuses
and a synagogue.
   No serious injuries were reported, but 45 firefighters suffered
minor eye injuries from flying embers, and five firefighters and two
civilians were treated for smoke inhalation, city fire spokesman Jim
Williamson said.
   ``We still face a very dangerous situation,'' Fire Chief Donald
O. Manning said as the fire eluded control at midafternoon in
non-residential lands close to other residential areas. ``We're not
out of the woods yet.''
   But by nightfall, the winds had begun to slack and the fire began
to calm. The National Weather Service predicted continuing weakening
winds, slowing to 10 mph to 15 mph by Saturday afternoon.
   The fire was 50 percent surrounded by 8 p.m. as it continued to
spread slowly northward into vacant hills, and full containment
expected by sunrise, said county fire spokesman John Lenihan.
   Fourteen houses and a mobile home were destroyed and 25 hours
were damaged Friday, said Fire Department spokesman Gary Svider,
putting the loss at $4.3 million. Earlier, officials had said 22
homes were destroyed or damaged, but a closer look at the burned
area resulted in the higher estimate.
   The fire raced from Sunshine Canyon through the Santa Susana
Mountains 25 miles northwest of downtown and down into the
fashionable Porter Ranch development, said county fire spokesman
John Lenihan.
   Helicopters braved fierce turbulence that made it difficult to
make water drops accurate, while vans carried ground crews up to the
battle. Fire trucks stood guard around an oilfield.
   Two firefighters were hospitalized for embers in their eyes, two
suffered from inhaling fumes of chlorine from burning pool supplies,
and 30 firefighters and one civilian suffered smoke inhalation,
Manning said.
   Seventy horses were evacuated to Granada Hills High School.
   The fire was reported about 4:30 a.m. by employees at the
Sunshine Canyon landfill above Granada Hills and an arson
investigation team searched for clues to the cause, said Battalion
Chief Dean Cathey.
   The fire swept southwest in a blizzard of embers to Porter Ranch,
where residents awakened to choking smoke and an orange glow in the
sky.
   ``It was just like raining fire,'' said Tim Dinsmore, 16, who
helped his father wet down the family home before they had to flee
several blocks away. ``As I was spraying water the neighbors' houses
started to burn; that's when I got scared.'' The Dinsmores' home
survived.
   ``Thousands of embers were coming down on us as we left,'' said
Hank Piorek, who fled the neighborhood with his family of four.
   The relative humidity fell to 15 percent, compared with a normal
60 percent in the early morning, the National Weather Service said,
and that combined with the wind and thick, dry brush to create an
explosive situation. ``Pound for pound, it's equivalent to
gasoline,'' Cathey said.
   Smoke streamed across the wind-swept sky as far as the Pacific
Ocean, 20 miles to the west.
   The chairman of the Los Angeles County Board of Supervisors, Ed
Edelman, asked Gov. George Deukmejian to declare an emergency in the
county so that fire victims can seek low interest loans to rebuild
homes and businesses.
   Elsewhere, wind fanned a 200-acre brush fire that broke out north
of Lake Elsinore, southeast of Los Angeles in rural Riverside
County, said state forestry spokeswoman Joanne Evans. Six aircraft
fought the flames in rugged terrain.
   The Dinsmores returned to find that they lost only a wooden
fence, while neighboring homes were destroyed.
   ``You should protect your property,'' said the elder Dinsmore.
``You should help the firemen. They take care of the big stuff, you
take care of the small stuff.''
   Mindy Piorek, 16, was shaken by the early morning evacuation.
   ``The garage was full of smoke, the cats were going crazy, I was
scared,'' she said.
   The Santa Anas are caused by the flow of air from high pressure
over the Western interior to low pressure offshore. Masses of air
pick up speed and warmth when they hurtle down from the desert,
squeezing through mountain passes into the Los Angeles Basin.
   Otherwise ordinary fires can be turned into firestorms that
hopscotch rapidly through brushland and residential areas.
   This blast of the Santa Ana wind began Wednesday, toppling
buildings under construction and overturning tractor-trailer trucks
on highways.
   Early Thursday, the suburbs of Baldwin Park and La Verne, east of
Los Angeles, were hit by fires ignited by downed power lines. At
least 22 homes were lost and 12 others were damaged, along with five
businesses. No serious injuries were reported but damage was
estimated at $10 million.
   Power outages hit about 500,000 people Wednesday night and
Thursday in Los Angeles, Orange, Riverside and San Bernardino
Counties. Rose Parade floats being built in Azusa were damaged when
a huge tent blew down.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
