<FILEID>AP-NR-12-10-88 0150EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-HouseBanking     12-10 0634</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-House Banking,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Banking Industry Doesn't Expect Revamping Of Laws Until 1990</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: St Germain with no period is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Banking Committee under a new
chairman likely won't act on legislation revamping the nation's
banking laws before 1990, some industry representatives say.
   ``All signals are slow,'' said Kenneth Guenther, executive vice
president of the Independent Bankers Association of America, which
is opposed to such legislation.
   The new House Banking Committee chairman, Henry B. Gonzalez,
D-Texas, said Friday that the issue of whether to permit greater
overlap of the banking and securities industries ``clearly ... must
be on the priority list.''
   Gonzalez added, however, at his first news conference since being
selected chairman Tuesday that he planned an extensive series of new
hearings on the subject and said the panel would start fresh in its
effort to write legislation.
   The committee, under outgoing chairman Rep. Fernand J. St
Germain, D-R.I., who lost his bid for re-election, started hearings
on bank deregulation last year. After a jurisdictional dispute with
the House Energy and Commerce Committee blocked the banking panel's
bill late in this year's session, St Germain pledged to re-pass it
``before the snow melts'' next spring.
   Gonzalez seems in no hurry to complete work on this legislation.
   ``You have to exercise as much or more care when you deregulate
as when you regulated,'' and ``fast legislation is dangerous
legislation,'' he said.
   Gonzalez has made the savings and loan crisis the committee's
first task and that, at best, will be resolved by August, Guenther
said. Then, if the Bush administration makes banking reform a
priority, it could become a focus of Congress in 1990, he said.
   Also, the new chairman of the Senate Banking Committee, Sen.
Donald W. Riegle Jr., D-Mich., is seen as more sympathetic to the
concerns of the securities industry than his predecessor, Sen.
William Proxmire, D-Wis., Guenther said.
   Robert Dugger, chief economist of the American Bankers
Association, which has pushed for additional bank powers, said the
S&L crisis is so compelling that Congress likely will deal with it
quickly.
   Although Gonzalez in the past has been skeptical of bank
deregulation, other members of the House committee are strong
advocates, he said, adding that a proposed series of regional
hearings on the issue need not delay action unduly.
   Gonzalez told reporters he intends to take testimony in January
on the nation's economy in preparation for writing new legislation.
Then, he said he wants the committee to hold hearings in each of the
12 Federal Reserve Bank districts around the nation to gather the
views of ``little bankers'' and ``citizens.''
   ``We want to hear from those voices who don't have a chance to be
heard in these great halls,'' he said. ``We have not had
comprehensive testimony other than from the lobbies.''
   On other topics, Gonzalez said:
   _The Federal Reserve Board, which operates independently of money
appropriated by Congress, should be held more accountable for the
power it wields over the nation's economy. Gonzalez is a long-time
critic of the Fed. He's advocated subjecting it to auditing by
Congress' General Accounting Office. In the early 1980s when the
board was fighting inflation with high interest rates, he called for
impeachment of the Fed chairman.
   _Industry proposals for resolving the savings and loan crisis are
``Santa Claus wish lists.'' Gonzalez, along with the S&L industry,
advocates tapping the Treasury to clean up insolvent S&Ls. However,
he proposes splitting off the industry's regulator, the Federal Home
Loan Bank Board, from the fund that insures its deposits. The
largest S&L trade group, the U.S. League of Savings Institutions, is
seeking to preserve the current regulatory structure.
   _The accumulation of corporate debt from leveraged buyouts is a
matter of ``great concern.'' But he offered no remedies.
</TEXT>
