<DOCNO> AP881210-0021 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-10-88 0216EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Chad-Sudan     12-10 0161</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Chad-Sudan,0166</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>100 Dead In Clash Between Chad Troops, Sudanese Rebels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chadian troops battled with rebels based in
neighboring Sudan, and the clash left 92 rebels and eight government
soldiers dead, according to Chad's foreign ministry.
   In a statement from Paris, the ministry said the skirmish near
Deguessa in eastern Chad was ``particularly violent.'' It said
Chadian troops in Thursday's action captured 15 trucks, mortars,
arms and ammunition.
   After years of fighting with Libyan troops and Libyan-backed
rebels, Chad agreed to a cease-fire last year with its northern
neighbor. The two countries recently renewed diplomatic relations
and exchanged ambassadors.
   But the Chadian statement was harshly critical of Sudan, which
shares a long border with this impoverished central African country.
   ``Hostile activities directed against Chad are prepared and
operate from the Sudanese province of Darfour, with the consent of
senior leaders in (Sudan's capital) Khartoum,'' it said.
   ``Chad condemns this unfriendly and bellicose attitude of the
Sudanese government.''
