<FILEID>AP-NR-12-10-88 0221EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0426 12-10 0809</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0426,810</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sununu Says Background Check Is Delaying Naming Of Bush's Defense
Chief</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to DELETE 2nd graf pvs, bgng: ``The
worst...'' and edit 4th graf pvs to conform; picks up 5th graf pvs,
bgng: ``You don't...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Incoming White House chief-of-staff John Sununu
says a thorough background check is delaying the naming of
President-elect Bush's defense secretary.
   Amid reports that an FBI check of top contender John Tower's
personal life is slowing down the process, supporters of the Texas
Republican said the delay could scar Tower politically.
   ``You always wish things could go faster,'' Sununu said Friday.
``And yet, in today's world, the worst thing you could do is to do
things quickly rather than thoroughly and that applies to all
appointments, not just the Tower one.''
   ``You don't get any extra credit for being early,'' the New
Hampshire governor said.
   Bush has yet to confirm widespread reports that Tower, who was an
arms negotiator for President Reagan and a former chairman of the
Senate Armed Services Committee, is his choice.
   However, a Bush transition source, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity, said Friday that Tower still appears to be Bush's first
choice.
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., a backer of Tower and adviser to Bush
on defense, indicated that a longer-than-anticipated FBI check was
stalling a final announcement. ``They (FBI) are checking allegations
and rumors _ womanizing, drinking involvement in defense
contracts,'' McCain said.
   ``All allegations have to be put to rest so there is no
embarrassment at a later date,'' he said in an interview. ``From
their viewpoint I wouldn't do anything different. It's just sad that
it's harming John Tower to some degree.''
   Sununu would not comment on the reason for the delay. But the
transition source confirmed it was primarily due to an FBI check
believed to be delving into the former Texas senator's personal life
and allegations made by his ex-wife.
   Bush on Friday continued meetings with various interest groups
and individuals. Benjamin Hooks, the head of the NAACP, said after a
private session with the vice president that Bush had promised to
put a black in his Cabinet.
   None of Bush's appointments yet has been a black. Hooks, who met
with the vice president for about 30 minutes, said the session was
``very cordial.''
   The vice president also met with a group of 13 prominent
conservatives. Edwin Feulner Jr., president of the Heritage
Foundation, said the group pressed Bush to ``make sure that all
parts of the (conservative) coalition continue to have a stake in
his success once he becomes president.''
   As for Tower, McCain expressed concern about the delay, saying,
``The longer it takes, there's bound to be an impact on his
stature.''
   Another supporter, Sen. William Cohen, R-Maine, said, ``I think
anyone who is allowed to hang out as the designated nominee without
any confirmation from the president-elect is bound to suffer a
thousand wounds.''
   Bush said this week he was ``disinclined to believe'' negative
allegations about Tower.
   A leading Democrat on defense issues echoed the sentiments of
Republicans McCain and Cohen.
   In a speech, House Armed Services Chairman Les Aspin, D-Wis.,
said: ``If Tower is named defense secretary, he will come into
office in a weakened position. ... For one thing, with all that
twisting in the wind, questions will be raised about how much
confidence the president has in him.''
   On other subjects, Sununu said:
   _He wants to be chief of staff ``for eight years with this
president'' and has no plans of returning to New Hampshire in two
years to run for office, although he is holding onto leftover
campaign funds for a possible future race.
   _Direct access to the Oval Office will be given to the chief of
staff, the deputy chief of staff and the national security adviser.
As for Vice President-elect Dan Quayle, Sununu said, ``They (Bush
and Quayle) are going to work out their arrangement, and obviously
whatever the vice president (Bush) decides is the way to work will
be the way we work.''
   _That, as reported, Bush adviser Robert Teeter had been offered
the post of deputy chief of staff and counselor to the president,
and was taking a few days to think it over.
   Teeter said in a telephone interview from his home in Ann Arbor,
Mich., that he would decide ``in the next few days'' whether to take
the job or return to Michigan to resume running his polling service.
``I don't know what I'm going to do yet,'' he said.
   Meanwhile, Charles Imbrecht, chairman of the California Energy
Commission, said Bush transition officials have spoken to him about
the posts of energy secretary and Environmental Protection Agency
administrator.
   ``I told them to make me an offer and we'll talk about it,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
