<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MarcosHospitalized 1stLd-Writethru a0430 12-10 0565</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Marcos Hospitalized, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0430,0581</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ferdinand Marcos Hospitalized</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 18th graf, ``The Philippine ...,'' to FIX spelling of
consul's name to Gomez, sted Gomze.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos
remained hospitalized after suffering congestive heart failure,
which aides said was triggered by concern for his exiled daughter.
   Marcos, 71, did not suffer a heart attack and did not require
surgery, doctors said, refusing to release other details until test
results were released later today.
   Marcos was in guarded condition late Friday after undergoing
tests, including an electrocardiogram, said St. Francis Medical
Center spokeswoman Norma Kop.
   He was expected to remain in the hospital's heart unit for about
two days, said Kop. She said he was in good spirits and that his
wife, Imelda, was receiving visitors in an adjoining room.
   Asked to comment on allegations that Marcos, who was deposed as
Philippine president in 1986 and is under indictment in the United
States, had earlier faked symptoms of illness, Kop replied, ``He had
a heart irregularity, and that can be pretty serious.''
   He was taken by ambulance to the hospital and admitted on the
recommendation of his cardiologist, Calvin Wong, due to ``the acute
onset of congestive heart failure'' early Friday, Marcos spokesman
Gemmo Trinidad said.
   Congestive heart failure means the heart is unable to pump the
amount of blood required by the body.
   ``Mrs. Marcos is very worried,'' Trinidad said. ``She's in tears;
she's always in tears.''
   Mrs. Marcos rode to the hospital in the ambulance. She clutched a
brown rosary and cried as Marcos was wheeled into the emergency room
on a stretcher.
   Marcos began having chest pains around 4 a.m., after learning
that his pregnant daughter, Imee Manotoc, who lives in exile in
Morocco, had labor complications and would deliver by Caesarian
section, Trinidad said.
   ``The president became so worried, sick and upset that they
called the doctor,'' Trinidad said.
   Marcos' eldest daughter delivered a boy, her third, but her
condition and that of the baby were not known, Trinidad said.
   Marcos was examined at his Makiki Heights home before being
hospitalized at 12:17 p.m., Trinidad said.
   Marcos aide Arturo Aruiza said doctors urged Marcos to seek
treatment for chest pains for the past three weeks, but he did not
want to be hospitalized because he thought critics would accuse him
of faking.
   ``If he thinks he can take the pain, he'll take it.''
   A New York cardiologist who examined Marcos has told a federal
judge in New York that although Marcos suffers various ailments, he
is well enough to travel to New York for arraignment on the
racketeering charges. The arraignment had been postponed after
Marcos' doctors said he was not well enough to travel.
   Marcos repeatedly faked pain during the three-hour examination,
according to the report by the cardiologist, Francis M. Weld.
   The Philippine consul general in Hawaii, Tomas Gomez, said he did
not believe Marcos was sick.
   ``Here we go again, the boy who cried wolf,'' Gomez said. ``With
all the publicity about his faking it. ... I really don't believe
him now.''
   The Marcoses are accused of plundering their homeland and
stashing millions of dollars in the United States. Mrs. Marcos
pleaded innocent on the charges, but Marcos has yet to be arraigned.
   They have lived in Hawaii since his 1986 ouster in a
military-civilian revolt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
