<HEAD>Soviets Outline Quake Relief Needs</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Quake Aid Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a list of items, mostly medical
equipment, that the Soviet Embassy in Washington says are needed for
the earthquake relief effort in Armenia.
   _Syringes
   _Blood transfusion systems
   _Antibiotics
   _Intravenous equipment
   _Instruments for bone reconstruction surgery
   _Cardio-pulmonary and anesthetic equipment
   _Medical and other equipment for rebuilding hospitals
   _Outpatient clinics, kindergartens, nurseries
   _Tents, blankets, clothing
   Soviet doctors are on the scene and no foreign medical personnel
are needed, said an embassy official, Yevgeny Kutovoi.
   The Soviet government also has established two special bank
accounts to handle contributions. One was at the Dupont Circle
Branch of the Riggs National Bank, 1913 Massachusetts Avenue, N.W.,
Washington, D.C., 20036. The name of the account is ``Earthquake
Relief Fund,'' and the number is 04-08-572-564.
   The Soviet Vnesheconbank in Moscow has also established a fund
for wire transfers. That account number is 70-000-412, said Kutovoi.
   Regular telephone lines at the Soviet Embassy are clogged with
calls and officials say they will set up special lines. A number has
not been announced.
   The American Red Cross has activated a toll-free number for
people to call to offer assistance: 1-800-453-9000.
</TEXT>
