<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Barbados-AIDS     12-10 0176</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Barbados-AIDS,0180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Caribbean Nations Get $12.4 Million To Fight AIDS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIDGETOWN, Barbados (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International donor countries and
organizations have pledged $12.4 million to 13 nations in the
Caribbean to help fight the spread of AIDS in the West Indies.
   The funds, to be supplemented with $7.4 million from the Caricom
nations, will go toward a three-year program of education on AIDS
prevention, research and purchasing equipment for the screening of
donated blood.
   ``The main thrust will be the reduction of sexual transmission
through intensive health education and the early detection and care
of persons infected with the AIDS virus,'' Barbados Health Minister
Branford Taitt said at the end of a four-day meeting of donor and
Caricom nations.
   The meeting was sponsored by Caricom, a group of 13 former
British colonies in the Caribbean, and the Pan American Health
Organization.
   Donor organizations and nations include the U.S. Agency for
International Development, the Canadian International Development
Agency, several U.N. agencies, the European Economic Community, the
International Red Cross, France, West Germany, Britain and the
Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
