<HEAD>Reagan to Speak at University of Virginia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan will make a major foreign
policy address next Friday at the University of Virginia, the White
House says.
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Friday that Reagan
would travel by helicopter to the UVA campus in Charlottesville,
Va., about 125 miles southwest of Washington, and give the speech to
some 700 students and faculty in Cabbell Hall.
   It will likely be Reagan's last major speech before he and first
lady Nancy Reagan fly to Los Angeles on Dec. 23 at the start of a
two-week Christmas and New Year's vacation there and in Palm
Springs, Calif.
   The speech in Charlottesville will be Reagan's second major
address of the week. The president will give a talk on domestic
policy Tuesday to federal officials and business executives at the
Constitution Hall of the Daughters of the American Revolution here.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Four Years Of Effort Leads To News Carrier Proclamation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newspaper deliverers are being honored at the
Carrier Hall of Fame with a new proclamation signed by President
Reagan and all 50 governors.
   The last signature on the document was added by the president
aboard Air Force One.
   After traveling from state to state in a mailing tube with a
special pen, the parchment proclamation suffered only a small
wrinkle in the upper right-hand corner, said Joseph Forsee, general
manager of the International Circulation Managers Association in
Reston, Va.
   It honors ``the young men and women who accept the responsibility
of distributing the daily newspaper.'' Forsee said more than 700,000
news carriers deliver morning and afternoon dailies across the
country, with about 70 percent of them children who earn from $20 to
$45 a week.
   Forsee said adult carriers, who tend to have larger routes,
deliver about half the newspapers in the country. Many unpaid
parents also help, he noted.
   Among those honored in the Carrier Hall of Fame are President
Eisenhower, Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, and Texas billionaire H. Ross
Perot.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Florida Party Leader Picked for Republican National Committee Post</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jeanie Austin, chairwoman of the Republican
Party in Florida, has been tapped to become the GOP national
co-chairman, officials announced.
   Ms. Austin will be formally elected at a Republican National
Committee meeting next month at which Lee Atwater's designation as
party chairman also will be ratified. Atwater served as campaign
manager for President-elect Bush.
   Ms. Austin has been active in Florida politics since 1970. A
retired American Telephone & Telegraph executive, she has held a
variety of party posts in her home state, including four years as
chairwoman.
   ``Great challenges confront us in the future but also great
opportunities,'' Ms. Austin said Friday. ``I am excited to be a part
of the movement that I believe can reposition our party as the
majority party in the future.''
   Atwater praised Ms. Austin as a ``political pro who delivers
results.''
</TEXT>
