<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Panama-USCrash     12-10 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama-US Crash,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Remains of Three Americans Killed in Honduras Arrive in Panama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAFAEL CANDANEDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The remains of three U.S. servicemen
killed in a helicopter crash in Honduras arrived at an American
military base in Panama and will be sent home after autopsies are
performed, officials said.
   A statement late Friday by the U.S. Southern Command said rescue
workers were searching for the bodies of two more servicemen, killed
Thursday when their CH-47 Chinook helicopter crashed near La Ceiba,
in northern Honduras.
   Charles Barclay, spokesman at the U.S. Embassy in Honduras,
identified the dead as 1st Lt. Alan C. Urban, Staff Sgt. John P.
McConnell, and Pfcs. Jim D. Bendon and Douglas J. Kropp, all based
at Fort Bragg, N.C.; and Chief Warrant Officer Randall B. Potter of
Fort Stewart, Ga.
   He did not release their hometowns.
   A team of investigators from the Army Aviation Center in Fort
Rucker, Ala., arrived in Honduras on Friday to seek clues in to the
cause of the crash, Barclay said.
   The Chinook was based at Palmerola Air Base. Barclay said it had
left Palmerola earlier Thursday on a supply run in joint
U.S.-Honduran military maneuvers.
   It was the second fatal crash this year of a twin-rotor Boeing
Chinook. On Feb. 25, an Army Chinook crashed near Chico, Texas,
killing 10 soldiers.
   At least 30 American troops in Honduras have been killed or
wounded in accidents or incidents of violence since the United
States began a series of exercises there in 1982.
   About 1,500 American troops are in Honduras, including 1,100
permanently stationed at Palmerola.
</TEXT>
