<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ArcticExercises     12-10 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arctic Exercises,325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Brigade, Reporters, Take Part In Sub-Freezing Practice</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DELTA JUNCTION, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 3,000 troops braved
Arctic weather to practice assault tactics designed for potential
attacks on Soviet positions, an exercise that also provided the
first test of the Pentagon's emergency media pool in such conditions.
   Three platoons of the 6th Light Infantry Division from nearby
Fort Greely took part in the maneuvers, 1,200 combat infantrymen and
1,900 support troops. Friday was the 11th day of a 15-day test of
men and equipment in temperatures that have plunged to 44 degrees
below zero. Winds at times have reached 70 mph, according to a media
pool report filed from the scene.
   ``This is probably the most physically demanding field troop
exercise the Army's ever put together,'' said Col. Jim Wood,
commander of the division's 2nd Brigade. Because of the winds,
helicopter maneuvers and air jumps were canceled.
   The conditions also were blamed for other problems, including
rifle jams attributed to exposure to bitter cold after being stored
in stove-warmed tents. Fort Greely, 100 miles southeast of
Fairbanks, is about an hour by plane from the Soviet Union.
   A small group of reporters was notified by the Pentagon just
after midnight Thursday and flown to Alaska from Washington. The
secret operation, a test of Pentagon procedures for bringing media
to combat areas in the event of hostilities involving U.S. troops,
was not disclosed until Friday afternoon.
   The pool arrangement was established following media complaints
after reporters were excluded from covering the U.S. invasion of
Grenada in 1983.
   The reporters were given a quick course in Arctic survival by
Army experts and provided with clothing and other equipment designed
for the frigid environment.
   The exercises are an annual event for the 2nd Brigade, the
northernmost U.S. combat troops in the world. Friday's activities
included live-fire assault accompanied by Air Force and Army
artillery barrages. The troops, provided with snowshoes and skis to
make their way through the fields, dug foxholes in waist-deep snow
banks and spent the night in the field.
</TEXT>
