<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     12-10 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PAXTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's hard to miss the community Christmas
tree. It rises 30 feet from a manhole in the center of an
intersection downtown.
   Even so, motorists in this town of about 4,200 people about 100
miles south of Chicago have been missing it for 25 years.
   ``I don't remember hearing any major complaints about it becoming
a traffic hazard,'' said Mayor James Kingston. ``We're all kind of
used to it.''
   Officials have anchored the Christmas tree at the same
intersection for at least a quarter of a century, said City Clerk
Millie Schroeder.
   ``We have a tree in the middle of the street every year,'' she
said. ``It's been in the center block I don't know how long.''
   Kingston said there's a good reason for the location.
   ``There's a big manhole right here in the middle of the street,''
he said. ``And, they place the tree in the manhole.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Carlucci family attracted more
attention than it expected, or wanted, by sending relatives a bogus
invitation to a White House dinner.
   The invitations to a recent family reunion were printed with a
fake Defense Department letterhead and the forged signature of
Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci.
   The Defense Department learned about the invitations, and the
Secret Service asked local police to investigate, said Maj. Anthony
Ciaccia of the Monroe County Sheriff's Department.
   Sheriff's deputies this week questioned several of the Carluccis,
who insisted the invitations were a prank.
   ``Needless to say, the local Carluccis are mortified and
apologized profusely,'' said Ciaccia. ``All's well that ends well.''
   ``It never occurred to us (that anyone would take it
seriously),'' said Mary Cilento of East Rochester, who helped send
out the invitations. The family held its reunion Nov. 25.
   Family members said they sent a real invitation to the defense
secretary, although they don't know if he is a relative.
</TEXT>
