<FILEID>AP-NR-12-10-88 0516EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Summit-LuncheonMeeting     12-10 0200</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Luncheon Meeting,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Wished Gorbachev Success With Economy, Report Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan and President-elect Bush assured
Mikhail Gorbachev at their meeting this week that they would not try
to undermine his program of economic change in the Soviet Union, The
New York Times reported today.
   During the leaders' luncheon meeting here Wednesday, Gorbachev
expressed concern that some in the West appeared to want his
economic program to fail.
   But the American leaders assured their Soviet counterpart his
fears were unfounded, the Times reported, quoting unidentified
Reagan administration officials.
   The sources said the superpower leaders discussed a number of
other topics, including priorities to set in the expanding arms
control talks, but neither side brought up new proposals.
   Gorbachev's sweeping decision to cut Soviet conventional forces
was not discussed, even though it had been the highlight of his
address only hours before at the United Nations, the sources said.
   The luncheon for top Soviet and American officials followed a
private meeting between Reagan and Gorbachev at which Reagan
reportedly gave Gorbachev a list of human rights cases.
   The earthquake in Soviet Armenia was briefly discussed at the
luncheon before the talk shifted to arms control.
</TEXT>
