<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DanceBan     12-10 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dance Ban,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Graduates Regret Missing High School's First Dance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA BRYSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PURDY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The music strikes up at Purdy High School
tonight, but some of the people who won a court battle against this
southern Missouri community's century-old dance ban won't be able to
get footloose.
   Only current students will be permitted to attend the homecoming
dance, disappointing graduates among the 21 students and parents who
sued two years ago to have the dance ban struck down.
   School Superintendent Sheldon Buxton, saying he feared outsiders
bent on disruption would be attracted by publicity about the dance
and dance ban, has restricted attendance to the 160 students
enrolled at Purdy High.
   ``Naturally that upsets me just a little bit, because most of the
people who were really behind it were in my class,'' said Amy Wolf,
who graduated last year.
   Amother graduate, George Fox, said he had planned to go to the
dance before learning administrators had put strict restrictions on
the event.
   ``But I can miss it _ I'm not going to let it upset me,'' Fox
said.
   U.S. District Judge Russell Clark ruled last summer that the
Purdy School Board's dance ban was unconstitutional, saying it
promoted the values of those who oppose dancing for religious
reasons.
   The school board appealed Clark's order, but suspended the
no-dance rule pending a ruling from the 8th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals in St. Louis. The appeals court is not expected to hear the
case until the end of the year.
   Miss Wolf, now a freshman at Missouri Southern State College in
nearby Joplin, recalls the homecoming games and crowning ceremonies
of her high school years _ followed by a 15-minute drive to a nearby
town for a dance. She said she had hoped for at least one dance in
the high school gym before graduating.
   ``I had no idea the court system would have taken so long to get
anything done,'' she said. ``I've learned a lot about the way
government works.''
   Fox's younger sister, Nancy, is student body president at Purdy
this year, and he has several other younger brothers and sisters.
   ``I'm not really sure if I got anything out of it or not,'' Fox
said of the court battle. ``But at least they (his siblings) will
get something out of it.''
   Purdy is a century-old farming community of about 900 people deep
in the Ozarks of southern Missouri and located about midway between
Springfield and Joplin.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881210-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-10-88 0530EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-StealthBomber     12-10 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stealth Bomber,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Department May Delay Peak Production of Stealth Bombers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Department is on the verge of
approving a change in funding that could delay peak production of
the B-2 stealth bomber until the mid- and late 1990s, the Los
Angeles Times reported today.
   The decision on the $68.5 billion stealth bomber program should
come Monday, the newspaper said.
   The Times quoted unidentified Pentagon officials who said the
bomber's production schedule ``clearly will be stretched out.''
   The news followed a meeting Wednesday of the Defense Resources
Board, the Pentagon's senior decision-making body for program
management.
   ``We've flattened out production to a more gradual increase than
was planned,'' a Pentagon official told the Times, requesting
anonymity.
   Air Force officials are backing the change in production, saying
it will allow time to incorporate improvements that may be suggested
during flight tests, the newspaper said.
   Deputy Defense Secretary William H. Taft IV, who chaired
Wednesday's meeting, was expected to reach a final decision over the
weekend following meetings with department officials, the Times said.
   Production plans call for building 132 of the planes.
   The stealth, a variation of a single-wing aircraft design and
resembling a giant bat, was unveiled last month when the first plane
was rolled out at Northrop Corp.'s production facility in Palmdale.
   The first bombers, costing $500 million each, were to be
delivered to the Air Force in 1991, with planes reportedly being
delivered at a rate of two per month by 1992.
   Production rates, like nearly everything regarding the highly
secret bomber, have been classified, but Taft's decision could push
back peak production two to three years.
   ``That production rate is now unaffordable,'' a defense official
said.
   Some lawmakers had also indicated previously that production
plans might have to be pushed back because of high costs.
   ``We probably are going to have to slow down the stealth ...
considerably,'' Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., chairman of the Senate defense
panel, said on CBS-TV's ``Face the Nation'' on Nov. 27.
   However, such a change could jeopardize the financial stability
of the bomber's prime contractor, Northrop Corp., which derives
about half its sales from the plane.
   The company already has reduced its labor force on the bomber
from a peak of 14,000 to 12,600 employees.
   As word that the bomber's production scale might be stretched out
began to surface on Wall Street last week, Northrop's stock dropped
from $31.875 a share to $29.125 in New York Stock Exchange trading.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
