<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ArmenianCommunity     12-10 0555</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Armenian Community,0573</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Armenian-American Community Shares Grief, Offers Aid</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Quake-Americans, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WATERTOWN, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of this little piece of Armenia
waited for news from their earthquake-devastated homeland as they
struggled to deal with the latest calamity to befall their people.
   ``It seems as though we're always being persecuted one way or the
other,'' said Carl Takvorian, 66.
   About 6,000 of Watertown's 39,000 residents are of Armenian
extraction. The tidy middle-class suburb about five miles west of
Boston is believed to have one of the highest concentrations of
Armenians in America.
   On Friday, the day after the quake hit Soviet Armenia, churches
were draped in black bunting, children laid wreaths at a monument,
and charitable organizations geared up to aid victims.
   ``We don't know why we're being punished,'' said retired
policeman Edward Kazanjian, 78.
   Kazanjian was one of dozens of people crowding the office of the
St. James Apostolic Armenian Church community center, awaiting any
news from the disaster area.
   ``The holocaust was bad enough,'' he said, referring to a Turkish
campaign to wipe out Armenians that began in 1894 and reached its
peak during World War I. Hundreds of thousands died, and many others
fled to the United States.
   The first feeling to sweep Watertown when word of the quake came
was despair, said Ara Kalaydjian, editor of the Armenian Mirror
Spectator.
   ``But now it's changed into determination to build again and not
for decades _ for centuries,'' Kalaydjian said.
   Friday morning, donors with checks and clothing and offers to
help raise money began arriving at St. James.
   People spoke of crying all night long. Children laid flowers at
the granite monument memorializing the Armenian massacre.
   When the tears dried, people put their energy into trying to
contact friends and relatives in the Soviet Union and to donate
money and other aid.
   The Armenian Assembly of New England was to begin a telethon
today to raise funds, and asked that donations of food and clothing
be brought to the TWA cargo hangar at Logan International Airport
for an emergency airlift.
   Armenians first settled in large numbers in Massachusetts in the
last century, when wire manufacturers in the central Massachusetts
city of Worcester recruited workers in the Near East, said the Rev.
Dajad Davidian, St. James' pastor. The first Armenian Apostolic
Church in the United States was established in Worcester in 1891.
   Some of those first settlers later moved to Watertown, then a
center of the rubber industry.
   On Friday, long faces spoke of shared grief and anxious hours
trying to get through to Armenia by telephone.
   Luda Esserian said she learned through a call that her sister,
Sofa, and her family were safe. The family lives in Stepanavan, an
Armenian village that sustained major damage. Although their home
was leveled, they were unharmed and are staying temporarily with
relatives in Yerevan.
   ``We listen to the radio all day,'' said Sonya Ourfalian, owner
of the Massis bakery, where shelves were stocked high with such Near
Eastern delicacies as dried figs and pastries heavy with honey.
   Though of Armenian extraction, Mrs. Ourfalian, 49, grew up in
Lebanon and has no relations in the Soviet Union. But she said the
feeling of connection with the quake victims runs deep.
   ``They are our people,'' she said. ``They are Armenians.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
