<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Korea     12-10 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea,0518</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hundreds Battle Police, March On Palace To Demand Chun's Arrest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of protesters demanding the
arrest of former President Chun Doo-hwan battled riot police today
with firebombs and rocks after they were blocked from marching to
the presidential palace.
   Radical students and dissidents fought police in the city's main
shopping district, tearing chunks of concrete from sidewalks and
pelting riot troopers with firebombs that burst in orange blasts of
blazing gasoline.
   ``Arrest Chun Doo-hwan! Overthrow (President) Roh Tae-woo!''
protesters shouted.
   Police had no figures on arrests or injuries, but officers and
protesters were seen with blood pouring from head wounds and other
injuries. Some police and protesters were brutally beaten after
being caught by the other side.
   Violence broke out when more than 2,000 people tried to march to
the Blue House presidential mansion after a rally at Myongdong
Cathedral.
   Dissident leaders announced at the rally the formation of a new
alliance to push for Chun's arrest and the overthrow of Roh.
Speakers said Chun could not be brought to justice while the Roh
government is in place.
   Riot police blocked the marchers with shields. Students with iron
bars and wooden clubs attacked police but were driven off by
tear-gas grenades.
   Hundreds of protesters regrouped several blocks away and attacked
police with firebombs. Police cleared the main streets several
times, but protesters repeatedly surged from backstreets and drove
the troopers back.
   Terrified people, many of them out Christmas shopping, fled as
firebombs and tear-gas grenades exploded around them. Riot police
chasing protesters hurled tear-gas grenades into subway stations.
   The protest was much smaller than three major violent protests in
Seoul last month to demand Chun's arrest for alleged corruption and
human rights abuses during his seven years in office.
   In another protest today, four Buddhist monks and 14 radical
students clashed with police several hundred yards from the remote
Buddhist temple on the east coast where Chun is in exile. The former
president went into exile after publicly apologizing for abuses
committed during his seven-year rule.
   The South Korean news agency Yonhap said fighting began when
police stopped protesters trying to approach the temple. Students
and police fought with clubs and six people were injured, Yonhap
said.
   Opposition leaders accused Roh of delaying action against Chun
and repeated demands that the former president cooperate with the
National Assembly probe of misdeeds under his rule.
   Kim Dae-jung, who heads South Korea's main opposition group, the
Party for Peace and Democracy, charged Roh with ``moving backward.''
   Another opposition leader, Kim Young-sam, urged Roh to
immediately remove all vestiges of the Chun era and take
``tangible'' measures such as releasing all political prisoners.
   Roh asked the nation to forgive Chun after the former president
apologized and went into internal exile.
   Chun, a former general who took power with military backing in
1980, stepped down in February at the end of a seven-year term. Roh,
another ex-general, won presidential elections last December.
</TEXT>
