<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     12-10 0578</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0592</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snow, Rain Keep Much Of The Nation Cold and Wet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Icy air streaming over the Great Lakes spawned snow squalls
throughout much of the Northeast today, with New York, Ohio and
Pennsylvania getting the brunt of the frozen precipitation.
   Most of the snow fell near lakes Erie and Ontario, with up to 6
inches of snow reported at Oswego, N.Y., and in the northeast corner
of Ohio.
   On Friday, up to 10 inches of snow blanketed West Virginia, over
the Mountain State's southern mountains and over the coal fields
near the Virginia border. Up to 10 inches fell across the mountains
of southwestern Virginia.
   In Tennessee, a twin-engine airplane carrying 40 pounds of
cocaine and $7,000 cash crashed into a snowy field outside
Knoxville, killing its pilot and a lone passenger. Police put the
cocaine's worth at $450,000.
   The plane was en route from Fort Lauderdale, Fla., to Dayton,
Ohio, with a fuel stop in Knoxville when it apparently lost an
engine, said Federal Aviation Administration spokesman Jack Barker
of Atlanta.
   Early today, snow stretched into northeastern New York and
northern and central portions of Vermont. In New York, snow fell on
portions of the Mohawk Valley, where heavy squalls were expected to
dump up to 6 inches of snow this morning.
   Elsewhere, light rain spread from southeast Arizona to southern
New Mexico and central Texas. Rain and snow were expected to become
more widespread as a slow-moving storm over northwestern Mexico
moved eastward. Some of the rain was expected to turn to snow, and
the mountains of southern New Mexico could receive more than 4
inches.
   Clear skies prevailed in the middle and south Atlantic states,
the Tennessee Valley and the central Plains.
   Today's forecast called for snow from Michigan to the northern
and central Appalachians; scattered snow through much of Montana;
snow or rain through western Texas; rain from central and eastern
Texas to the lower Mississippi Valley; and fog in California's San
Joaquin Valley.
   High temperatures were forecast in the single digits and teens
from northern New England to northern New York, the upper Great
Lakes, the upper Mississippi Valley and parts of the Dakotas; the
40s and 50s from the Carolinas to the Tennessee Valley, the Gulf
Coast states and much of Texas, and from the southern Rockies to the
Pacific Northwest; the 60s and 70s over much of California and the
desert Southwest, from the 60s to the 80s over the Florida
peninsula; and in the 20s and 30s elsewhere.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 14
degrees below zero at Warroad, Minn., to 70 degrees at Key West
Naval Air Station, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 31 partly cloudy; Boston 27 fair; Buffalo 23
cloudy; Charleston, S.C. 35 fair; Cincinnati 25 cloudy; Cleveland 22
cloudy; Detroit 21 snow; Miami 66 fair; New York 30 fair;
Philadelphia 25 fair; Pittsburgh 21 fair; Portland, Maine 16 fair;
Washington 28 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 03 snow; Chicago 28 cloudy; Dallas-Fort Worth
40 cloudy; Denver 19 fair; Des Moines 24 cloudy; Indianapolis 28
cloudy; Kansas City 32 partly cloudy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 07 fair;
Nashville 24 fair; New Orleans 49 fair; St. Louis 31 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 31 cloudy; Anchorage 38 showers; Las Vegas 44
fair; Los Angeles 56 fair; Phoenix 55 rain; Salt Lake City 29 foggy;
San Diego 55 fair; San Francisco 50 fair; Seattle 48 rain.
   _Canada: Montreal 00 fair; Toronto 19 snow.
</TEXT>
