<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan     12-10 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nippon Executive Resigns In Connection With Stock Scandal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An executive of Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp.
was dismissed from his job in connection with a stock scandal that
led to the resignation of the finance minister.
   Ei Shikiba, director of the telephone giant's data communications
department, was relieved of his duties but will remain an executive
director of the company with no specific responsibilities, company
president Haruo Yamaguchi said Friday.
   Shikaba was dismissed for buying unlisted shares in Recruit Co.,
the parent company of the Recruit-Cosmos real estate company.
   Aides of more than a dozen influential politicians reportedly
earned large profits by buying unlisted shares in Recruit-Cosmos and
then selling them after they were publicly listed in October 1986.
   Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa resigned Friday after making
conflicting statements regarding the scandal.
   He initially testified to a parliamentary committee investigating
the scandal that a third party, a friend of his former secretary,
purchased 10,000 Recruit-Cosmos shares and only borrowed the name of
``Miyazawa.''
   He later admitted his ex-secretary actually paid 30 million yen,
or about $246,000, for the shares in September 1986 and sold them
for 52.7 million yen, or $431,000, less than a month after they were
listed.
   Miyazawa also insisted the stock purchase was not financed by a
Recruit-linked financial institution but refused to show bank
documents to back up his argument.
   NTT, Japan's largest telephone company, has been criticized for
its close ties with Recruit, which reportedly include the leasing of
large numbers of telephone circuits at reduced rates and the resale
of two U.S.-made supercomputers.
   Shikiba had previously admitted purchasing 5,000 shares of
Recruit-Cosmos stock but did not notify the company of his
acquisition of Recruit shares, news reports said.
   Opposition parties have demanded a full investigation into the
stock scandal and have blocked parliamentary debate on a proposed
tax overhaul to press their demands.
   Miyazawa, who had been under political fire for weeks, said he
was resigning to pave the way for the tax reform.
   After Miyazawa's resignation, the governing Liberal Democratic
Party set a timetable for debate on the tax reform bills. If
deliberations are carried out smoothly, the package will pass before
Dec. 28, when the current parliamentary session is due to end.
   The legislation, Japan's first sweeping overhaul of its tax
system since the end of the World War II, has been a top priority
for the Liberal Democratic Party for a decade.
   Successive administrations have failed to pass the reform due to
a lack of public support and strong resistance from opposition
parties.
   The new package simplifies corporate and personal income tax
scales and introduces a 3-percent sales tax.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
