<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Lebanon-Israel 1stLd-Writethru   12-10 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0481,0514</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Death Toll At 10 From Israeli-Lebanese Fighting</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with two grafs to correct town location. Picks up graf
3
pvs, `Three Israeli ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The death toll from Israel's deepest
incursion inside Lebanon in five years rose to 10 after a
Palestinian guerrilla died of his wounds, police said today.
   Eight other guerrillas and an Israeli officer were killed Friday
in nine hours of air, sea and ground combat in hills overlooking the
coastal town of Naameh, nine miles south of Beirut.
   Three Israeli soldiers were injured and 16 guerrillas were
wounded, including one who police said died during the night in a
hospital.
   Lebanon requested an urgent meeting of the U.N. Security Council
to debate the attack, which drew sharp condemnation from the United
States and Britain.
   The Israeli raid coincided with the first anniversary of the
Palestinian uprising in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip, in which at least 320 Palestinians and 11 Israelis have been
killed.
   The target of the raid was a major base of the Popular Front for
the Liberation of Palestine-General Command in the Naameh bluffs, 50
miles north of the Israeli border.
   It was the first time the Israeli army had come so close to the
Lebanese capital, Beirut, since it evacuated the Chouf mountains
southeast of the city in 1983, ending a yearlong occupation.
   Israeli paratroopers were dropped from helicopters in to a ravine
below an abandoned Maronite Catholic monastery and attacked the
living quarters and training center of the guerrillas, Lebanese
police said.
   The Israelis used dogs strapped with tear-gas canisters and
explosives to flush out guerrillas from an underground network of
tunnels, Popular Front commander Ahmed Jibril told reporters.
   One of his aides, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
Palestinian fighters shot and killed five dogs.
   Several previous Israeli air attacks this year have failed to
eliminate the Popular Front's Naameh base.
   The radical Popular Front, which opposes Palestine Liberation
Organization chairman Yasser Arafat, is armed by Syria and
bankrolled by Libya.
   During the fighting Friday, four Israelis were cut off from the
main landing force, prompting the Israeli command to mount a massive
rescue operation.
   Waves of Israeli fighter-bombers thundered in on rocketing and
strafing runs and naval gunboats shelled Naameh's highlands until
the four Israelis were ferried out of Lebanon at mid-morning,
clinging to the struts of two helicopter gunships, an Israeli army
officer said.
   The Israeli raid was the second biggest in terms of casualities
this year. At least 40 Palestinian and pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem
guerrillas were killed when the Israeli army mounted a three-day
sweep in southeast Lebanon in May.
   In both attacks, Syrian troops stationed close to guerrilla bases
did not intervene in the confrontations.
   The Syrians maintain about 40,000 troops in north and east
Lebanon as well as Beirut's Moslem sector under a 1976 Arab League
mandate to control Lebanon's civil war, now in its 14th year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
