<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Quake-Witness     12-10 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quake-Witness,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reporter Saw Only Dust Rising From Quake-Shattered City</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet-Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A reporter six miles from the shattered Soviet city
of Leninakan said today an earthquake has changed the landscape of
the region, which once was dotted with buildings and sparkled with
city lights at night.
   Now, looking at Leninakan from the Turkish border, ``all you can
see is a sort of hazy mist, almost a cloud ... rising from the
rubble and ruins of the town,'' Jane Howard of the British
Broadcasting Corp. said in a radio broadcast.
   Ms. Howard said she went to the border after arriving Friday at
the northeast Turkish town of Kars, 40 miles from Leninakan, one of
the cities hit hardest in Wednesday's killer earthquake. About
250,000 people lived in Leninakan, the second-biggest city in the
Armenian republic.
   ``From the border you could actually look across and see the
town,'' Ms. Howard said. ``(The earthquake) really does seem to have
changed the whole landscape of the area.''
   ``I was there when dusk fell and whereas last week you would have
been able to see bright lights from street lights and security
points along the border, there was only a very faint glow there last
night (Friday),'' she said.
   ``The one thing you can hear on the border is a sort of almost
constant low rumble. It is the drone of transport planes flying
relief supplies in.
   ``Occasionally you hear a helicopter or see the light of a
helicopter going in, although most of the relief operation is being
mounted from (the Armenian capital) Yerevan... Clearly they are
mounting a huge 24-hour operation over there,'' the report said.
   Yerevan is about 60 miles southeast of Leninakan.
   Ms. Howard said the temperature in the area has been below
freezing but that there was no snow on the ground.
   She said there was very little damage on the Turkish side of the
border.
</TEXT>
