<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PTL     12-10 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PTL,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bakker Planning TV Specials</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PINEVILLE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Viewers will see a new Jim Bakker when the
founder of the PTL television ministry and his wife tape several TV
specials from their living room, one of his attorneys said.
   ``I think we'll see a more introspective and cautious Jim Bakker
in his message,'' attorney Jim Toms said Friday. ``His new public
ministry will be targeted not just to Christian charismatics but to
hurting people.
   ``He has a lot to share about what he has learned,'' Toms said.
   Jim and Tammy Bakker plan to tape several TV specials from the
living room of their 14-room log cabin near Pineville, Toms said.
   ``He's hoping to get on the air in the next 30 days,'' he said.
   Bakker has not had a regular TV show since he resigned from the
ministry in March 1987 in the wake of a sex-and-money scandal. He
has been preaching recently at a converted skating rink in
Charlotte, where his New Covenant Church is based.
   Bakker has not spoken publicly since his indictment Monday on
federal fraud and conspiracy charges. Bakker, 48, and a top aide at
PTL are accused of diverting more than $4 million of PTL money to
support their own ``lavish and extravagant'' lifestyles.
   PTL, in bankruptcy reorganization since June 1987, must sell its
assets to pay creditors. A federal bankruptcy judge in Columbia,
S.C., has scheduled an auction for Monday.
   Toms said Bakker will likely preach Sunday about what he has
learned from his experiences. ``My expectation is that he'll be
there (at the church) and he'll have something to say,'' said Toms.
``Getting his message out is important.''
</TEXT>
