<2ND_LINE>PM-Deaths, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0479,0126</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS last graf to include title of fourth novel. No PM
separates moved.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Robert Bright</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Bright, who wrote and illustrated
``Georgie the Ghost'' books that entertained children since the
1940s, died Nov. 21 of cancer. He was 86.
   Bright wrote 21 children's books and four adult novels. He was a
reporter for the Baltimore Sun and then worked for the Paris office
of the New York Herald-Tribune in the 1920s.
   Bright's first ``Georgie the Ghost'' book was published in 1944.
He wrote his last ``Georgie'' book when he was 81. His adult novels
were ``The Intruders,'' ``The Olivers,'' ``The Spirit of the Chase''
and ``The Life and Death of Little Joe.''
</TEXT>
