<FILEID>AP-NR-12-10-88 0751EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Quake 2ndLd-Writethru   12-10 0880</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Quake, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0470,0910</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Arrives In Armenia, Officials Say 40,000-45,000 Dead</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout with Gorbachev arriving in Leninakan, French
team saving 60, details. No pickup. TRIMS to edit and conform.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos WX7, WX10, WX11 and NY5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev arrived today in
Armenia where search dogs, medical teams and rescue workers
struggled to save men, women and children buried in the rubble of an
earthquake that officials say killed at least 40,000 people.
   After a three-hour flight from Moscow, Gorbachev landed in
Leninakan, a city of 290,000 where more than three-fourths of the
housing, including multi-story apartment buildings, was destroyed.
   The government declared a day of national mourning. Across the
country, hotels, campgrounds and private homes were opened to
survivors of the quake.
   Soviet officials said today that 1,500 people had been rescued
from ruins where they had been trapped since the earthquake struck
Wednesday.
   The official news agency Tass said today that French teams
working with Soviet rescuers had saved 60 people.
   Health Minister Yevgeny I. Chazov said time was running out on
those still trapped by the quake, which measured 6.9 on the Richter
scale.
   The first official death toll was released today when Deputy
Foreign Minister Valentin Nikiforov said that according to ``the
first preliminary information, 40,000-45,000 people died as a result
of the earthquake.''
   In nearby Turkey, the governor of its eastern province on the
Soviet border, Hasan Pakir, was quoted by Anatolia News Agency as
saying, ``Next door to us thousands of people died. We escaped a
possible catastrophe.''
   He said only four people died in Kars province from the quake.
   The toll is lower than that estimated Friday by Leonid Zamyatin,
the Soviet ambassador to Britain, who estimated 80,000 people had
been killed.
   Nikiforov told a news conference today that 12,000 people were
injured and nearly 7,000 are hospitalized, many with burns and
crushed limbs when the quake struck Armenia, a republic of 3.3
million 1,200 miles southeast of Moscow.
   ``Everything that could burn was burning,'' after the quake hit,
Council of Ministers spokesman Yuri P. Chapligin said. Throughout
the area, electrical appliances, gas stoves, and industrial fuel and
explosives ignited after the shock, he said.
   The first Western planeloads of doctors, search dogs and medical
supplies arrived Friday as people from around the world joined a
rescue effort made extraordinary because it occurred in a land
normally closed to foreigners.
   In Moscow, authorities were preparing to take in 10,000 children
whose parents' whereabouts apparently were unknown, the Communist
daily Pravda reported. Private families have offered to take in
orphans and injured adults, the newspaper said.
   The Armenian community, however, is ``indignant,'' fearful such
measures may permanently separate children from parents who may
still be alive, said Bishop Tiran Durakyan of the Armenian Church in
Moscow.
   Firefighters said they pulled about 80 people out of the rubble
in Leninakan, Armenia's second-largest city.
   ``In these conditions, delaying by each hour means an additional
20 killed of every thousand concealed under debris. Such is the
terrifying arithmetic,'' Chazov told the newspaper Izvestia.
   Tass provided a damage report from the stricken region. According
to the report:
   _The hardest-hit cities were Leninakan, Krovakan, Stepanavan and
Spitak. Spitak and its surrounding villages were ``demolished
practically altogether.''
   _All of Leninakan's 1,100 privately owned houses were damaged or
destroyed.
   _Hundreds of apartment buildings collapsed in the cities of
Kirovakan and Stepanavan.
   The influx of worldwide aid was unprecedented for the Soviet
Union. After the 1986 Chernobyl disaster, U.S. doctors were the only
foreign aid personnel allowed in.
   Cuba on Friday sent 32 tons of medical supplies, and President
Fidel Castro was one of the first to donate blood.
   A U.S. cargo plane left Washington today to deliver medical
supplies and canine search teams. The operation marks the first
large-scale U.S. government assistance to Soviet Union in the
post-World War II era.
   British fashion designer Katherine Hamnett said her firm was
donating $14,700 in heavy woolen fabric for blankets and warm
clothing.
   Muscovites donated money at their workplaces.
   Soviet television showed rescuers combing flattened buildings,
carefully removing blocks of concrete to search for survivors. A
correspondent said the workers could hear voices below.
   ``Somewhere here is my brother,'' said a man standing in the
debris. ``He worked as a factory director. He came home during a
break and stayed here. Children are here ... and father, they just
took him away. They took him to his funeral.''
   Smoked wafted from the rubble and the man added in a hoarse
voice: ``I don't know, maybe they (the children) already burned up
here because we haven't been able to extinguish this fire for
several days. Oh, the grief is terrible.''
   In London, Independent Television news carried a voice report
from Stella Gregorian, an American student at Yerevan University.
   She said she saw ``people only digging for people who they heard
voices from. If they heard no voices they are going on to places
where they can hear voices. There are countless, countless people
underneath these buildings that they can't get to.''
   Flags flew at half-staff and entertainment activities were
canceled because of the national day of mourning. Armenian leaders
had declared Friday and today days of mourning in their republic.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881210-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-10-88 0821EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Nobel 2ndLd-Writethru   12-10 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nobel, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0474,0568</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Chief Accepts Nobel, Chides U.S. For Failing To Pay Dues</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout with medal presented.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY GERBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Nations' chief today accepted the
Nobel Peace Prize on behalf of U.N. peacekeeping troops but warned
that their mission is threatened because the United States and other
nations don't pay their dues.
   ``Peacekeeping uses soldiers as servants of peace rather than as
the instruments of war. It introduces to the military sphere the
principle of non-violence,'' U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de
Cuellar said.
   His hands appeared to shake with emotion as he received the gold
medal and prize certificate from Egil Aarvik, chairman of the Nobel
Committee. Aarvik noted that it was the first time in the prize's
87-year history it was awarded to military forces.
   Perez de Cuellar said 733 men have been killed since U.N.
peacekeeping operations began in 1948. In all, about 500,000
soldiers from 58 countries have served in the forces, and 10,000 are
now on duty.
   One of them, U.S. Marine Lt. Col. William Higgins, is held
hostage in Lebanon, the U.N. leader noted, and he appealed for
Higgins' release.
   ``Never before in history have military forces been employed
internationally not to wage war, not to establish domination and not
to serve the interests of any power or group of powers, but rather
to prevent conflict between peoples,'' Perez de Cuellar said.
   ``There is a new mood of understanding and common sense,'' said
Perez de Cuellar, who was accompanied by an honor guard of the
blue-bereted peacekeeping soldiers.
   The U.N. chief cited progress on U.N. efforts to end the
Iran-Iraq war and conflicts in Afghanistan, the Western Sahara,
southern Africa and elsewhere.
   On Friday, Perez de Cuellar accepted the monetary portion of the
award _ $416,000 _ a fraction of the $450 million in dues owed by
U.N. members.
   ``I don't know how we're going to cope financially,'' he said.
``In some ways it's embarrassing because it forces me to say
publicly that the United States still owes the United Nations almost
$350 million.''
   The United States has withheld dues in recent years to protest
what the Reagan administration saw as mismanagement, overstaffing
and anti-Western bias at the 159-member body. President Reagan said
in September the United States would gradually repay all its dues.
   Asked when the U.N. would pay its own peacekeeping force bills to
Norway, Denmark, Britain, Canada and other countries that provide
troops, Perez de Cuellar said: ``They are all understanding. They
think we are honest people. But unfortunately, not everyone is
honest with us.''
   In a report this week, Perez de Cuellar predicted the world body
would end next year with a loss of $24.6 million. Only 79 members
had paid all their dues by Nov. 30, the report said.
   He said Friday that the Soviet Union owed about $100 million, but
he praised the Soviets for setting a payment schedule and sticking
to it.
   The Nobel check is usually presented after the medal ceremony,
but Perez de Cuellar had to fly immediately to Paris after the
ceremony for the 40th anniversary of the U.N. Human Rights
Convention.
   The medal ceremony is always held on the anniversary of the Dec.
10 death of Swedish philanthropist Alfred Nobel, the inventor of
dynamite.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
