<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Lebanon-Hostages     12-10 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Hostages,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shiite Cleric Says Hostages' Issue On Ice</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An influential Shiite Moslem cleric was
quoted today as saying the question of foreign hostages in Lebanon
is ``in the fridge'' while the issue is investigated.
   ``The question (of the hostages) is now in the fridge, pending
the completion of backstage probes that could influence the issue,''
said Sheik Mohammed Hussein Fadlallah, spiritual guide of the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God. He did not elaborate.
   Fadlallah was quoted by the An Nahar Arab and International, a
weekly based in Christian east Beirut. None of the magazine's
previous reports about the hostages have proved accurate.
   Hezbollah is believed to be the umbrella for Shiite extremist
factions holding most of the foreign hostages.
   Fourteen foreign hostages are being held in Lebanon, including
nine Americans. The longest-held is Terry Anderson, chief Middle
East correspondent for The Associated Press, who was kidnapped March
16, 1985.
   In addition, Peter Winkler, a Swiss Red Cross worker, was
abducted Nov. 17 in southern Lebanon, but no group has claimed
responsibility.
   In a separate report today, An Nahar said Hezbollah had
threatened to kill some of the hostages to stop attacks on its
positions in west and south Beirut by the rival, Syrian-backed
Shiite Amal militia last month.
   The magazine did not identify the hostages Hezbollah allegedly
threatened to kill or give further details.
   The rival factions have long been vying for dominance of the 1
million Shiites who make up the largest single sect of Lebanon's
population of 4 million.
</TEXT>
