<1ST_LINE>r i PM-PLO-Arafat     12-10 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PLO-Arafat,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arafat Calls On Palestinians To Escalate Uprising</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONA ZIADE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PLO chief Yasser Arafat today called on
Palestinians in Israeli-occupied territories to escalate their
year-old uprising and warned the Israelis planned to intensify
measures to choke it off.
   In a message to the ``masses'' in the West Bank and Gaza Strip in
honor of the anniversary of the uprising, Arafat declared: ``You are
recording a new victory in the march toward liberation with every
daybreak.''
   The text of the Arabic-language statement was released by the
Palestine Liberation Organization's office in Cyprus.
   Arafat said: ``You have made them (the Israelis) feel the chains
of international isolation and the bankruptcy of their occupation
policy.
   ``But, my loved ones, you must be on alert as they undoubtedly
will resort to escalating the criminal, oppressive measures of their
so-called `iron fist' policy, as well as the aggression against our
refugee camps.
   ``As we near victory,'' the PLO chief said, ``We must realize
that the most ferocious and bloody confrontations occur in the last
quarter of an hour before peace.''
   Arafat has often said that sustaining the intefadeh, or uprising,
would eventually force Israel and the United States to deal with the
PLO and endorse the Palestinian quest for an independent state.
   Since the Palestinian uprising began on Dec. 8, 1987, 322
Palestinians and 11 Israelis have been killed.
   In his speech, Arafat made no reference to his latest peace
overtures, including recent statements that some have interpreted as
explicit recognition of Israel's right to exist.
   He spoke only of the Nov. 15 declaration in Algiers by the
Palestine National Council, the PLO's parliament-in-exile,
proclaiming an independent Palestinian state in the West Bank and
Gaza and calling for a two-state solution that divides
British-mandate Palestine into Jewish and Arab states.
   The United States has refused to deal directly with the PLO until
it recognized Israel and renounced terrorism. The United States and
Israel have said recent PLO statements are insufficient.
   ``What we aspire is Palestinian peace, not an Israeli or American
peace,'' Arafat said.
   ``We want peace that guarantees our legitimate political rights,
foremost of which our right to return, to self-determination and to
our independent state with Jerusalem as its capital.''
   The message, signed ``your brother Abu Ammar,'' Arafat's nom de
guerre, ended with a verse from the Koran, Islam's holy book, that
says patience leads to ``victory over the infidels.''
   In another development today, a planned march in honor of the
uprising at the University of Jordan in Amman turned into a
stone-throwing brawl between Palestinian and Jordanian nationalists.
At least one person was injured, officials said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
