<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Czechoslovakia-Dubcek 1stLd-Writethru a0498 12-10 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Czechoslovakia-Dubcek, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0498,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dubcek Says He Was Under House Arrest During Mitterrand Visit</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of Mitterrand throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Communist Party leader
Alexander Dubcek, ousted after leading a 1960s reform movement, said
today he was under house arrest during the visit of French President
Francois Mitterrand.
   Dubcek told reporters police cars circled his home in the hills
overlooking Bratislava on Friday, when Mitterrand was visiting the
city, and that he could not leave home.
   Dubcek's wife, Anna, told reporters that the police were gone
today and her husband could leave the house.
   It was the first time Dubcek has been kept under such close watch
since April 1987, when Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev visited
Czechoslovakia and routine police surveillance of the ousted
communist leader was abruptly lifted.
   Dubcek, who inspired the reform movement that was quashed when
Warsaw Pact troops marched into Prague in 1968, had been kept under
constant surveillance since he returned home in 1970 from his
five-month term as ambassador to Turkey. He was expelled from the
Communist Party and given a low-level bureaucratic job from which he
is now retired.
   During his two-day visit to Czechoslovakia that ended Friday,
Mitterrand praised the leaders of the ``Prague Spring'' reforms
inspired by Dubcek, but the former communist leader did not meet the
French president.
   Last month, Dubcek was allowed to leave Czechoslovakia for the
first time in 18 years, traveling to Italy to receive an honorary
degree at Bologna University.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
