<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Italy-Raphael     12-10 0169</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Italy-Raphael,0173</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Experts To Examine Work Said to Be Raphael Self-Portrait</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Experts are examining a painting recently found in
Venezuela to determine if it is a self-portrait of the Renaissance
master Raphael.
   The painting, the property of an unidentified Venezuelan
millionaire, was sent to Italy so its origins could be investigated,
Italian press reports said.
   The work measures 19 by 14 inches and is painted on canvas, the
Italian news agency AGI reported. The Italian Ministry of Culture
named a committee to examine the painting, and the panel began its
work Friday.
   The work was spotted in Venezuela by an Italian professor, Nico
Nicosia, dean of the State Institute of Art in Urbino, Raphael's
hometown in northern Italy. Nicosia says he would like to see Italy
acquire the work.
   Raphael, whose full name was Raffaello Sanzio, lived from
1483-1520 and worked as a painter and architect. He helped in the
reconstruction of St. Peter's Basilica and won fame for his fresco
work in the Vatican.
</TEXT>
