<FILEID>AP-NR-12-10-88 1041EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SmellyChristmas     12-10 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Smelly Christmas,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City Raises Stink Over Christmas Trees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WESTMINSTER, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stealing an evergreen tree from city
property to use as a Christmas tree could cost a person a lot of
friends. The trees have been sprayed with a smelly brew of fox urine
and skunk scent.
   ``Last year was the first year we did this, and we didn't lose
any trees,'' said park foreman Larry Pruegner. ``We're hoping that
it would be successful this year. If we save even one tree, then
we've more than done our job.''
   Westminster used to lose 15 to 20 of its Colorado blue spruces
and pines a year to people who helped themselves. Replacing a tree
cost between $120 to $160, plus the cost of planting.
   But last year parks director Jerry Royther heard about the
University of Nebraska using fox urine to prevent thieves from
cutting down the trees on campus, and he asked the staff to look
into it.
   ``I thought it was hilarious,'' Pruegner said. ``But when you
think about it, it may not seem as funny as it sounds.''
   He said he decided to add the skunk scent on the advice of Rocky
Mountain Enterprises in Fort Collins, which sells it to trappers.
   ``They told me, `If you really want to make the concoction right,
put this in, it's pretty rank, too,''' he said.
   It's so rank, he warned his staff: ``You need very good rubber
gloves to prevent the stuff from getting on your hands, and be
especially attentive to how the wind is blowing.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
