<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TeamstersDissident     12-10 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teamsters Dissident,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Awards Dissident Union Member $552,000.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Teamsters Union dissident who accused
union officials of violating his rights for years has been awarded
$522,000 in damages by a federal court jury.
   Arthur Doty, of Newburyport, contended in his lawsuit that he was
harassed, assaulted and threatened because of his work with a group
called Teamsters for a Democratic Union. He said he was denied his
constitutional and union rights by officials who ``engaged in a
purposeful and deliberate attempt to discourage dissent within their
unions.''
   ``I hope to God this makes Teamster officials all over the
country think twice before they start pushing around people who are
fighting for their rights,'' said Doty, 42, a Teamsters member for
nearly two decades who is no longer a member of the union.
   Friday's jury verdict included damages from Teamsters Local 42 in
Lynn and several past and present officers.
   In addition, Doty's attorney, Mark Stern, said Local 49, one of
three locals that denied Doty membership after he joined the
dissident group, agreed to pay Doty $20,000 immediately and $20,000
over the next five years and to apologize.
   Teamsters for Democratic Union group says it seeks democracy and
an end to corruption in the union.
</TEXT>
