<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0494 12-10 0611</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0494,0627</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Troops Shoot and Kill Two Palestinians</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 10th graf, All 650,000, to UPDATE with
quotes from Arafat statement. Pick up 11th pvs, `In Arab east...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops shot and killed two Palestinians
today, including a 16-year-old boy who threw a firebomb at a patrol
in occupied Gaza City and an Arab prisoner who attacked a guard with
a makeshift knife, the army said.
   At least 12 Palestinians were shot and wounded, Arab hospital
officials said.
   The 16-year-old Gaza boy, Hosni Abu Sido, was part of a gang of
youths who threw gasoline-filled bottles at soldiers patrolling Gaza
City this morning, just hours after a curfew was lifted and
residents were allowed outside, the army spokesman said.
   ``The lives of the soldiers were in danger and the commander of
the patrol opened fire,'' said the army spokesman, who is not
identified according to regulations.
   He said a soldier was lightly wounded but did not require
hospitalization.
   The prisoner killed, Abdallah Abu Mahruka, attacked a guard with
a makeshift knife while he and fellow inmates in Gaza City's Shati
prison were out on a daily walk.
   The deaths raised the number of Palestinians killed in the
year-old anti-Israeli revolt to 322. Eleven Israelis also have been
killed.
   At 11 a.m., Gaza City storekeepers closed shop and traffic stood
still for five minutes of silence in memory of the Palestinians
killed in the uprising, which began Dec. 8, 1987.
   About 250,000 Arabs were confined to their homes in Gaza refugee
camps for the third straight day. A curfew was lifted from Gaza City
and small villages, the army spokesman said.
   All 650,000 residents of the Gaza Strip were under curfew Friday
to prevent violence surrounding the first anniversary of the
uprising.
   In a statement released today in Nicosia, Cyprus, PLO chief
Yasser Arafat called on Palestinians to escalate their uprising,
telling them: ``You are recording a new victory in the march toward
liberation with every daybreak.''
   ``As we near victory,'' Arafat said, ``we must realize that the
most ferocious and bloody confrontations occur in the last quarter
of an hour before peace.''
   He did not mention his recent peace initiatives, including
statements interpreted by some as explicit recognition of Israel's
right to exist.
   In Arab east Jerusalem today, police fired tear gas and rubber
bullets to disperse demonstrators who threw rocks in the Arab
commercial center near the walled Old City and in an Arab village
and refugee camp, both in the city limits. There were no injuries,
police said.
   Police arrested seven girls in another clash in East Jerusalem,
which began when a police van was stoned and one of windows smashed.
   In northern Israel, arsonists caused serious damage when they set
a mosque on fire in the Israeli Arab village of Ibtin near the port
city of Haifa, Israeli radio said.
   An anonymous telephone caller told police he set the fire to
punish Ibtin residents, 10 of whom were accused last week of being
members of an anti-Israeli guerrilla squad. The suspected
guerrillas, all Israeli citizens, were accused of throwing a hand
grenade that blew the leg off a Haifa boy in July.
   Hospital officials said seven Palestinians were shot and wounded,
most of them in the legs, in the Gaza Strip today.
   Five other Palestinians were shot and wounded in the occupied
West Bank, hospital officials said. Most of the clashes reportedly
occurred near Nablus, the West Bank's largest city.
   Palestinians in the Gaza Strip and West Bank have been under
military occupation since the 1967 Middle East War, when Israel
captured the territories from Egypt and Jordan.
</TEXT>
