<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Emperor     12-10 0160</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Emperor,0171</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hirohito Continues Bleeding, Receives Transfusions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito received a series of transfusions
today to control his internal bleeding and his condition remained
unstable, said a palace spokeman.
   Doctors said the 87-year-old monarch hemorrhaged heavily late
Friday and early today and they extracted blood from his upper
digestive tract through a tube, according to Imperial Household
Agency spokesman Kenji Maeda.
   Maeda said the emperor received about two pints of blood since
Friday night. His systolic blood pressure fell to 90 in the morning
and rose to 110 in the evening, Maeda said. A normal reading is
about 120.
   Maeda said this morning that the emperor's condition had ``not
restabilized.''
   Hirohito has received a total of about 53 pints of blood since he
became ill Sept. 19, when he started bleeding from the part of the
intestine that was operated on last year.
   Palace officials refuse to confirm or deny that the emperor has
cancer.
</TEXT>
