<FILEID>AP-NR-12-10-88 1055EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica     12-10 0696</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa,0715</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Ambassador, Senators Criticize Botha And Rights Abuses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Ambassador Edward Perkins
condemned South Africa's human rights record Saturday, and two U.S.
senators warned of tougher sanctions after a ``deeply
disappointing'' meeting with the president.
   Perkins, the first black U.S. ambassador to South Africa, said in
a Human Rights Day speech that security laws ``are being used in an
ever more political manner.'' He described the policy of detention
without trial as ``one of the worst kinds of human rights abuse.''
   The other featured speaker at the Johannesburg meeting was the
Rev. Frank Chikane, a former detainee who is general-secretary of
the South African Council of Churches. Perkins has had extensive
contacts with black opposition leaders during two years in South
Africa but rarely has he shared a podium at a major public event
with a militant activist such as Chikane.
   In Cape Town, Sens. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., and David Boren, D-Okla.,
told a news conference they were pessimistic about South Africa
after completing a one-week fact-finding trip. They met numerous
government and opposition leaders.
   The senators, both influential committee chairmen, said President
P.W. Botha bluntly rejected their request to meet with imprisoned
African National Congress leader Nelson Mandela, one of the top
priorities of their trip.
   ``He (Botha) gave a very rapid answer _ `No, you're not.' We
repeated the question, and got the same answer,'' Boren said.
   Boren, chairman of the Senate Intelligence Committee, described
Tuesday's meeting with Botha as ``the deepest disappointment'' of
the trip.
   ``We came as centrists, as constructive people, hoping to talk to
the state president about the future of the country,'' Boren said.
``The state president deeply disappointed us, by wanting to talk
only about the past, not trying to engage and assess and share ideas
about the future.''
   If Botha's attitude was seen in Washington as representative of
government views, intensified economic sanctions were likely, Boren
said.
   The senators, in a prepared statement, said Botha's government
had taken some positive steps, including tentative approval of an
accord to bring independence to Namibia and release of some
political prisoners.
   ``In all candor, however, we must say that the pessimism which we
feel comes from the alarming direction currently being taken by the
government,'' the statement said.
   It cited the recent treason convictions of four anti-apartheid
leaders after a three-year trial and intensifying restrictions on
opposition activity.
   ``If those who are working for real change are foreclosed from
using non-violent political methods, it is our great fear that they
will be forced to turn to methods that will undoubtedly lead to
violence and tragedy,'' the senators said.
   Perkins last week attended the final session of the treason
trial, in which four activists received prison sentences ranging
from 6 to 12 years.
   ``Court decisions which convict genuine, non-violent community
leaders of treason and terrorism cannot be expected to command
respect,'' he said.
   One of the activists whom the senators met was Albertina Sisulu,
wife of jailed ANC leader Walter Sisulu. She is not allowed to make
public statements or engage in political activity.
   ``To be free means you can speak your mind and your conscience,''
said Boren. ``It is unbelievable to me, having met people like Mrs.
Sisulu, how any kind of government keeps a person under those
conditions.''
   Nunn, chairman of the Senate Armed Forces Committee, said he
would support tougher U.S. sanctions if a vote were taken now. But
he added that in respect to forcing change in South Africa, ``you
can't say sanctions have succeeded.''
   Chikane, speaking after Perkins at a Johannesburg church, read a
letter which he said was sent covertly by black detainees. It said
the government was conducting ``a concerted campaign of
disinformation'' to convince Western leaders that reform was
occurring.
   President Reagan and British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher
``continue to buy our repression at the cheapest rate of exchange,
and we hold them equally liable for our deteriorating conditions,''
the letter said.
   Human Rights Day marks the 40th anniversary of the United
Nations' adoption of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights.
South Africa abstained rather than support the document.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
