<DOCNO> AP881210-0080 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-10-88 1110EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BellRinger     12-10 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bell Ringer,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Impostor Steals Salvation Army Kettles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELLEVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Someone who believes it is better to
receive than to give has stolen about $600 in Salvation Army
donations and kettles by posing as a collector for charity bell
ringers.
   ``He had all the credentials it takes'' to be a bell ringer, said
Salvation Army Lt. Nathan Johnson, head of the charity's Belleville
office. ``It's believed he was hired as bell ringer this year, and
had been hired in the past.''
   ``It saddens me, because I obviously hired the person,'' Johnson
said Friday.
   No arrests have been made.
   Bell ringers at three stores in the area east of St. Louis
reported that a man wearing a Salvation Army bell-ringer badge and
carrying a bell approached them Wednesday and told them he was there
to collect money from their kettles, Johnson said. All three workers
refused to hand over their kettles.
   But the thief succeeded at a grocery store when two women bell
ringers, following Salvation Army policy, left their kettles at the
store's customer service counter while they went to the restroom,
Johnson said.
   The impersonator showed his badge to store employees and told
them he was there to pick up the kettles. The man then fled with
kettles and money worth about $600, Johnson said.
   ``We don't hold the store in any way responsible,'' he said.
   Despite the theft, the Salvation Army's holiday campaign in the
Belleville area has collected about $54,000 of its $200,000 goal,
Johnson said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
