<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BRF--CostlySmoke     12-10 0144</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Costly Smoke,0147</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lung Cancer Patient Lights Up, Causes Hospital Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAFAYETTE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lung cancer patient who lit a cigarette
while inhaling pure oxygen caused a fire that burned him and forced
evacuation of other patients at University Medical Center.
   ``We discourage patients from smoking in their room, and they
usually don't. We tell them if they must smoke, smoke with an
attendant present,'' said George de Gravelle, UMC's acting
administrator.
   Patient George Stickler, 59, of Broussard, suffered second-degree
burns on his back Friday and his bed was destroyed, said fire
inspector Robert Benoit.
   Eleven other patients on the same floor were evacuated before
hospital personnel put out the blaze with fire extinguishers. Benoit
estimated damage at $3,000.
   A state fire marshal's investigation was ordered because a
sprinkler in the patient's room didn't work when the fire started,
Benoit said.
</TEXT>
