<DOCNO> AP881210-0082 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-10-88 1114EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Nixon:TheInsideStory Bjt   12-10 0937</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nixon: The Inside Story, Bjt,950</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nixon Papers Stuffed With Tidbits, But No Bombshells</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Things no one would know if the National
Archives didn't release a new batch of papers from Richard Nixon's
White House once in a while:
   That Ronald Reagan once considered Carla Hills, President-elect
Bush's choice to be U.S. trade representative, too liberal for a
senior federal post. That CIA director Richard Helms made points
with his boss by sending complimentary little notes, such as one
critiquing a televised speech as ``most impressive in the best
presidential tradition.'' J. Edgar Hoover did, too.
   That among the Americans who praised Nixon for his Saturday Night
Massacre of officials during the unraveling Watergate scandal were
hotel magnate J. Willard Marriott and former Milwaukee Braves
baseball manager Fred Haney. That Henry Kissinger stiffed a Cabinet
member who wanted help in getting his son a visa for China.
   And that a fifth grader got Nixon's attention with his profiles
of former presidents like ``Martian V. Buran.''
   These and other tidbits were gleaned from a comparatively modest
550,000 pages of Nixon administration files which the National
Archives opened to public view last week. Modest, in the sense that
there are 40 million in all, of which only 5 million have been made
public so far.
   No bombshells in this batch, just insights.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Haldeman! Ehrlichman! Look At This:</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   On Feb. 22, 1973, Nixon wrote a former neighbor in San Clemente,
Calif., thanking her for sending along son Robbie's profiles of
former presidents. ``I shared his comments ... with some of my staff
members and we all agreed that Robbie had a most direct, no-nonsense
approach to history.''
   And what had Robbie written? ``Martian V. Buran was first
American born after the revolutionary war. Martian was a friendly
man.'' And of ``Milliard Fillmore:'' ``One day he went to school. He
had a woman teacher and after school he married his teacher.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Dear Mr. President: How Great Thou Art</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Nixon's mail was full of laudatory notes from officials who owed
their jobs to him.
   One was Richard Helms, who was trying to hang onto his job as
head of the CIA. He often wrote the president after public
appearances and once sent him a package of peaches. In one of his
notes, Helms wrote:
   ``Without, I hope, being thought presumptuous, may I say how
effective I found your appearance on television last evening. You
were persuasive and constructive ... and it came over as a most
impressive performance in the best presidential tradition. It gave
even me a big lift.''
   After a Nixon speech on drugs, Helms promised that his agents
would ``bust their buttons to improve intelligence collection on the
drug traffic.''
   Helms' efforts didn't work. At the end of his first term in 1972,
Nixon replaced Helms and made him ambassador to Iran.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>I Need A Favor, Henry</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   In the spring of 1973, Attorney General Richard Kleindienst's
son, Alfred, was working temporarily at the U.S. consulate in Hong
Kong. He wanted to visit mainland China at a time when the United
States did not have formal diplomatic relations with that government.
   Kleindienst approached Kissinger, the wizard who had wrangled an
invitation to China for Richard Nixon. Receiving no answer from the
national security adviser, Kleindienst put his request in writing.
Kissinger's staff asked if he wanted to help or send a ``polite
turndown.''
   Kissinger chose a third route: ``Sit on it.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Return of the Closet Liberals?</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush, who made the L-word a dirty word in his campaign,
intends to nominate Carla Hills to be U.S. trade representative in
his Cabinet. Bush might be interested to know that 15 years ago,
just before Nixon nominated her to be an assistant attorney general,
a White House aide wrote colleagues who were weighing the
nomination: ``Governor Reagan has cleared her for this position, but
has not endorsed her. She is considered a liberal by Reagan's
standards.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>A New CIA Plot Revealed</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   From John Ehrlichman, the No. 2 aide in the White House, to
Rogers C.B. Morton, secretary of the interior. Memo, dated Feb. 21,
1972:
   ``It has been brought to the attention of the White House that
the statue in front of the Justice Department on Constitution Avenue
is actually that of Nathan Hale, who, as you know, was executed by
the British on 22 September 1776.''
   It occurred to Ehrlichman that Hale had no connection with the
Justice Department and, as more of a spook than gumshoe, he would be
more at home at the CIA.
   ``The Agency Operations Division point out that a clandestine
removal is entirely feasible and is now temporarily planned for the
dark of the moon during the month of March,'' Ehrlichman wrote.
``Workmen will be disguised as paperboys, Department of Commerce
secretaries headed home after working overtime, GSA trash removal
men and tourists. The actual removal is planned via a three-ton
truck disguised as a wholesale bread delivery van.''
   Ehrlichman said he had been empowered to let Morton in on this to
ensure that Morton's Park Police ``will not fire upon the agency
workmen during this operation. ... It is felt best if clandestine
support is given to this operation by causing blank rounds to be
issued to all Park Police.''
   There is no evidence of a reply from Morton in the Nixon files.
Nathan Hale still stands outside the Justice Department. Maybe
Morton got the joke.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Associated Press Writers William M. Welch and
Harry F. Rosenthal helped read through thousands of documents to
find these nuggets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881210-0083 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-10-88 1116EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Italy-USDeaths     12-10 0159</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Italy-US Deaths,0163</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three U.S. Soldiers Killed in Car Accident</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Feild in 2nd graf is cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>VICENZA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three U.S. Army paratroopers died when
their car went off a bridge and landed upside down in a river, the
Army said Saturday.
   A fourth paratrooper, Spec. Jose Martinez of Houston, was not
injured, said an Army spokesman, Lt. Col. Frank E. Feild.
   Feild, spokesman for the Southern European Task Force in the
northern city of Vicenza, said the Army would withheld the names of
the dead.
   He said the accident occurred midnight Friday in downtown Vicenza
when the off-duty officers' car crashed through the railing of a
one-lane bridge.
   ``Initial reports indicate that the three soldiers drowned,''
Feild said, adding that an autopsy would be performed Monday.
   The Army will conduct an investigation into the accident, he said.
   All four soldiers were assigned to the Combat Support Company of
the 3rd Batallion, 325th Regiment, in Vicenza.
</TEXT>
