<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Egypt-Fundamentalists     12-10 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Egypt-Fundamentalists,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>About 100 Injured In Clashes Between Rival Moslem Groups</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASSIUT, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fundamentalists at odds over how to
implement Islamic law clashed among themselves and attacked police
this week, killing one officer and leaving about 100 people injured,
official sources said today.
   Tension remained high among students belonging to the extremist
Moslem group known as Gamaat Islamiya and the moderate Brotherhood,
who fought Wednesday and Thursday with knives, chains and sticks,
said the sources, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   In the Ein Shams district of Cairo on Thursday and Friday,
extremists attacked the police station with stones and flaming
objects, and 50 of them were taken into custody, the sources said.
   Police said today they mounted a nationwide search for an
extremist suspected in the stabbing death of police Lt. Col. Essam
Shams on Thursday in Ein Shams.
   The Interior Ministry identified the assailant as Sherif Mohammed
Sherif, 27, a clerk at a Cairo high school who belongs to the
underground group known as Jihad. The government has blamed Jihad
for the assassination of President Anwar Sadat on Oct. 6, 1981, and
a failed coup attempt two days later organized from Assiut.
   Since the clashes, security forces swept the Ein Shams district
of Cairo and detained more than 130 extremists, said the security
sources in the capital.
   The clashes started at the university in Assiut, 237 miles south
of Cairo, which for years has been a center of Moslem extremist
activity.
   Followers of Brotherhood and Gamaat have been feuding for months
over religious differences such as which side should be allowed to
deliver sermons in the mosques.
   Both moderates and extremists support implementation of Sharia,
the Islamic legal and ethical code that was introduced about 14
centuries ago in the Moslem holy book, the Koran.
   Extremists advocate using violence, if necessary, in support of
the Moslem laws, while the Brotherhood says it is in favor of
peaceful action. The government contends more than 90 percent of
Egyptian laws already conform to the laws of Islam.
</TEXT>
