<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDSGrants     12-10 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Grants,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foundation To Give $16.7 Million in AIDS Grants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A private foundation will give $16.7 million in
AIDS grants to organizations in 25 states, including a project to
provide foster care in Kansas for AIDS-infected infants from New
York and California.
   Fifty-four projects in 25 states, Puerto Rico and the District of
Columbia will receive amounts ranging from about $5,000 to more than
$1.8 million, said the Robert Wood Johnson Foundation of Princeton,
N.J.
   The grants will be formally announced Monday.
   A $70,185 grant will go to a Salvation Army program in which
infected infants from areas with high incidence of AIDS will be
placed with foster families in Wichita, Kan. It is often difficult
to find foster care for infected infants within high-incidence
communities, leaving them unnecessarily hospitalized, the Johnson
foundation said.
   Girls Clubs of America, Inc., will receive $211,975 to develop a
guide and education materials for member clubs to use in educating
girls about risks of acquired immune deficiency syndrome.
   Other money will go for giving AIDS education and medical care to
homeless people in Los Angeles, promoting AIDS prevention among
migrant and seasonal farm workers in Delaware, Maryland and
Virginia, and training 240 teen-agers in Chicago to educate peers
about AIDS.
   Additional grants will support AIDS education for 1,300 youths in
runaway shelters in southeastern states, free legal services for
AIDS patients in New York hospitals, and a California study of
techniques to encourage condom use.
</TEXT>
