<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Health     12-10 0571</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Health,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Doctors Say Reagan is Cancer-Free and in `Excellent' Shape</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors pronounced President Reagan cancer-free
and ``in excellent health'' Saturday after laboratory tests on a
polyp removed from his colon, the White House reported.
   ``No further examinations or tests are required. The president is
in excellent health,'' said the statement issued by presidential
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater.
   The 77-year-old president was spending the weekend resting at his
mountain retreat at Camp David, Md., with his wife, Nancy. He was
informed of the final results by his physician, Col. John Hutton.
   ``The tissue removed Friday afternoon from President Reagan's
colon for biopsy is benign,'' the statement said.
   It identified the small amount of tissue taken from the president
as ``a benign adenomatous polyp,'' a type of growth that is often
found in men of Reagan's age.
   The president and Mrs. Reagan traveled to Bethesda Naval Medical
Center in suburban Maryland for their annual physical examinations
Friday afternoon, and for routine checks intended to detect any
recurrence of their past cancers.
   The president had a two-inch cancerous lesion removed from his
colon in July 1985. The first lady had her left breast removed last
year after a quarter-inch malignancy was discovered.
   Mrs. Reagan, 67, was told Friday that her second breast X-ray
since that surgery revealed ``no evidence of cancer of any kind.''
   Leaving the hospital after a four-hour visit, the president and
his wife both smiled and gave thumbs-up signs, and Reagan called out
``clean bill of health'' to reporters. He still wore a pair of blue
running shoes for stress tolerance tests that required him to walk a
treadmill.
   Shortly after the tests, Hutton said in a statement that doctors
had removed a ``small piece of tissue'' from Reagan's colon and that
it ``appeared to be benign'' or non-cancerous but was removed
because it was ``suspicious.''
   There are several kinds of benign growths that can occur in the
colon, and they generally are divided into two types _ hyperplastic
or adenomatous polyps. Hyperplastic polyps usually are not thought
to be associated with cancers elsewhere in the colon, while
adenomatous polyps are a signal to be on guard for future growths.
   Reagan's doctors have told him that he will need periodic colon
tests for the rest of his life.
   The president has had polyps removed from his intestine in four
of five colonoscopic exams since the cancerous lesion was removed
from his colon three years ago. These small polyps tend to occur
more frequently as people grow older, and can become cancerous if
left alone.
   Hutton said the colonoscopy was performed without sedation.
   This technique involves use of a long, flexible scope that is
inserted into the bowel. If a polyp is found, the physician can use
a tiny wire loop at the end of the scope to snare the growth and
clip it off. The wound is sealed with an electrical current
delivered by the instrument.
   The statement said the president's chest X-ray was clear, his
urine sample was normal and there was ``no clinically significant
change'' in his pulmonary condition.
   ``The stress test and electrocardiogram showed the president's
cardiovascular system is unchanged and normal,'' it said.
   Reagan's CAT-scan, the computerized three-dimensional X-ray of
his internal organs, showed no internal abdominal abnormalities. The
test checks against the spread of cancer to other vital organs such
as the stomach or liver.
</TEXT>
