<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Paraguay     12-10 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Paraguay,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Block Human Rights March In Paraguay</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Human Rights, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEDRO SERVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police attacked hundreds of people with
electric prods and rubber batons Saturday to prevent them from
holding a march to commemorate the 40th anniversary of the Universal
Declaration of Human Rights.
   Several dozen people were reported injured, including Rafaela
Guanes de Laino, wife of arrested opposition leader Domingo Laino;
and Ilde Silvero, director of the Roman Catholic weekly publication
Sendero.
   Several demonstrators were arrested.
   Police prevented people from entering the national cathedral,
where a pre-march Mass was celebrated at noon, and dispersed a crowd
of 300 at the office of the United Nations. The groups were to have
marched between the two buildings in downtown Asuncion, which was
packed with shoppers.
   When about 700 people gathered again at the U.N. office, security
forces waded into the crowd and beat demonstrators and shoppers.
   The incident quickly turned into a demonstration against the
president, Gen. Alfredo Stroessner. The government had banned the
march, saying it was intended as an anti-Stroessner protest.
   ``The military dictatorship is going to fall!'' the demonstrators
chanted. ``The people, united, can never be defeated!''
   Small groups of protesters gathered at streetcorners, chanting
anti-government slogans and then dispersing before police could
attack them.
   ``We should keep fighting for the effectiveness and respect of
human rights in Paraguay, within the framework of non-violence,''
Carlos Romero Pereira, a leader of dissidents within the governing
Colorado Party, said in front of the ABC-Color newspaper building.
The paper was closed by the government in 1984.
   Euclides Acevedo, president of the opposition Revolutionary
Febrerista Party, said the repression of the marchers reflected
Paraguay's ``prehistoric state of authoritarianism'' under
Stroessner's 34-year rule.
   The march was organized by groups representing students, unions,
churches and opposition political parties.
   The universal declaration, adopted without dissent by the General
Assembly on Dec. 10, 1948, is the basic U.N. document under which
member nations pledge to safeguard life and liberty and abolish
torture and slavery.
</TEXT>
