<HEAD>Peace Prize Not First Nobel For U.N.-Related Groups</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Nobels, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 1988 Nobel Peace Prize to U.N.
peacekeeping forces was the eighth peace prize for individuals or
agencies related to the world organization. Here is a list of the
winners:
   1949 _ Lord John Boyd Orr of Britain. Prominent organizer and
director-general of the United Nations' Food and Agriculture
Organization.
   1950 _ Ralph Bunche of the United States, honored for his role as
U.N. mediator in the 1948 Palestine conflict. He was later appointed
U.N. Deputy Secretary-General.
   1954 _ Office of the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees for
international relief work.
   1961 _ Dag Hammarskjold of Sweden. The prize was awarded
posthumously to the former U.N. secretary-general, who died in a
plane crash in 1961.
   1965 _ The U.N. Children's Fund, UNICEF, for international relief
work.
   1969 _ The International Labor Organization for promotion of
social justice and human rights for working people.
   1981 _ Office of the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees for
international relief work.
   1988 _ The U.N. peacekeeping forces for contributions to reducing
tensions where an armistice has been negotiated but a peace treaty
has yet to be established, and for contributing to the initiation of
peace negotiations.
