<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Quake-Volunteers     12-10 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quake-Volunteers,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Volunteers Work Day and Night to Ship Packages to Armenia</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For three days and nights, Agam Adamyan and scores
of other Moscow volunteers have packed and loaded tons of clothes,
bedding and baby food to ship to earthquake victims in Armenia.
   Unshaven and haggard, Adamyan appeared a man with a mission
Saturday as he scurried through winding corridors of the Armenian
government building, directing newcomers to the basement where
cardboard boxes and black plastic bags of donations reached the
ceiling.
   Plump Russian women carrying bulging suitcases mingled in the
lobby with dark-haired Armenians who raced around looking for string
and the rare roll of packing tape.
   ``We're getting lots of help from Moscow residents,'' Adamyan
said. ``People are coming of their own initative. Everybody here is
a volunteer, and Armenians and Russians are working together.''
   When a Russian receptionist said the director of the office was
very busy and asked a reporter to leave the premises, Adamyan
stepped in and said, ``Those are not objective grounds. Come take a
look at what we are doing.''
   The relief effort is unusual for the Soviet Union because it is
spontaneous and voluntary rather than ordered by officials.
   Black ribbons marking two days of official mourning in Armenia
fluttered from the ends of flagpoles holding the Armenian and Soviet
flags above the pale yellow Armenian government building, located a
10-minute walk from the Kremlin in central Moscow.
   In one room, Armenian and Russian university students chattered
and sorted through mounds of children's clothes, stuffed animals and
boxes of baby food and tossed them into the appropriate boxes.
   ``Above all, we have got to get more children's food and blankets
for the homeless,'' Adamyan said. Pillows, thick wool blankets and
heavy comforters are piled in another room.
   Outside the building, other volunteers tossed packages onto a
waiting bus from the Soviet travel organization Intourist to be
taken to the airport.
   So far, the volunteers have dispatched more than 20 tons of
donations to Yerevan and have said they will stay as long as people
continue to donate.
   At least three other collection points have been set up in the
Soviet capital by the Komsomol, the Communist Party youth
organization, and representatives of the Armenian church in Moscow
met to intensify relief efforts.
   Volunteers also are manning an around-the-clock telephone
switchboard to field inquiries to the Armenian government offices.
   A page of typewritten verses from an anonymous Moscow poet hung
on the bulletin board at the entrance to the building.
   ``I saw the mountains of Ararat (where Noah's Ark supposedly
landed) and there was trouble and the tremor of the Earth. And I am
with you brother,'' wrote the poet, who signed his lines simply as
``Muscovite.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881210-0101 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-10-88 1431EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-China-Tibet 1stLd-Writethru a0548 12-10 0892</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Tibet, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0548,0917</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Troops Fire On Tibetans, Apparently Killing Two, Tourists Say</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with official confirming
injuries. Pickup 9th graf pvs ``The demonstration came...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese troops in the Tibetan capital shot into
crowds of people demonstrating for human rights Saturday, apparently
killing two people and wounding three, including a Dutch woman,
witnesses said.
   An official at the Tibetan Foreign Affairs office in Lhasa, Zhu
Jianhua, said police fired warning shots in the air and hit some
people by accident but he did not know how many. Zhu said he could
not confirm the report of deaths.
   In a report late Saturday, China's official Xinhua News Agency
said a group of Buddhist monks and nuns ``started a riot in Lhasa''
but it said nothing about casualties.
   The Xinhua report said the nuns and monks walked from one temple
to the central market near the Jokhang Temple, one of the holiest
sites of Tibetan Buddhism, and were joined by other people.
   ``On the way, some other people joined in. Some of them were seen
waving flags in support of the independence of Tibet,'' the report
said.
   ``As the crowd grew unruly, policeman on duty began to take
measures to stop the marchers, who were later dispersed,'' the
report said.
   It was the third time since last year that blood has been shed in
Lhasa during demonstrations by Tibetans against Chinese rule.
   Protests in October 1987 and March left at least 38 people dead,
dozens injured and hundreds arrested.
   The demonstration came as the Chinese government and Tibet's
exiled leader, the Dalai Lama, were exchanging proposals about a
possible meeting in Geneva to discuss ways of bringing peace to the
remote Himalayan region.
   The demonstrators, who were commemorating the 40th anniversary of
the U.N. Declaration on Human Rights, gathered before noon in front
of the Jokhang Temple, said two Western tourists at a Lhasa hotel
and a Tibetan worker.
   The witnesses, reached by telephone from Beijing, said protesters
holding the banned Tibetan flag entered the marketplace near the
temple and crowds of Tibetans surged toward them. Chinese troops
opened fire on the crowd and Tibetans threw rocks at the Chinese.
Tear gas filled the air, sending protesters fleeing, the witnesses
said.
   About an hour later, the protesters returned but were dispersed
again after Chinese troops fired guns in the air, they said.
   ``About 30 Tibetans walked into the marketplace near the temple
at around 11:30 a.m.,'' said Lucia Dezries, of Urk, the Netherlands,
who said she witnessed the events. ``They were walking in twos. The
first man was holding a Tibetan flag. A crowd in the marketplace
began to encourage them. Then the soldiers began shooting.''
   The crowd began pelting the soldiers with rocks, but it was not
clear which came first, the rock-throwing or the shooting, she said.
   Ms. Dezries said a 25-year-old woman, also from the Netherlands,
was shot in the arm by Chinese forces and hospitalized but was not
seriously hurt.''
   She said she saw two Tibetans lying in pools of blood. ``Later
two Westerners told me that they had died,'' she said.
   ``I saw women carrying their bodies,'' said the Tibetan worker at
another hotel, who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``I have been
told they are dead.''
   An American tourist, contacted at another hotel, said she
witnessed the demonstration and believed that two people had been
killed. She declined to give her name.
   The deaths could not be independently confirmed.
   Ms. Dezries said she also saw two Tibetan women being helped from
the marketplace with what appeared to be bullet wounds in their
legs. ``They were both bleeding and they couldn't walk,'' she said.
   Ms. Dezries said she did not see police arrest any Tibetans.
   After the demonstration, Ms. Dezries said, pilgrims continued to
pray around the Jokhang Temple. Two pools of blood lay on each side
of the temple, and Tibetans placed stones on the blood along with
candles and sticks of incense.
   Ms. Dezries quoted monks as saying there would be more
demonstrations Sunday, but she said police told tourists the Jokhang
Temple would be closed for three days.
   She said it was not clear whether the Tibetans participating in
the demonstration were Buddhist monks because they all were in
street clothes.
   Monks have traditionally been at the head of Tibet's independence
movement, and have led a series of anti-Chinese protests beginning
in September 1987.
   At least 14 people were killed Oct. 1, 1987, when a protest
turned into an attack on a local police station. In March,
pro-independence Tibetans clashed again with police, and Western
travelers quoted Tibetans as saying at least 24 people died. Chinese
reports said hundreds were arrested.
   Chinese officials have said most of those arrested in the October
and March protests have since been released.
   Communist Chinese troops entered Tibet in 1950. Tibetans rose up
in a mass rebellion in 1959 but Chinese troops crushed them, and the
current Dalai Lama fled to exile in India.
   The Dalai Lama said in July that he was willing to accept Chinese
control over Tibet's foreign affairs and a Chinese military presence
there if China would give the region autonomy in domestic matters.
China rejected the proposal, but in September said it was willing to
meet with him.
</TEXT>
