<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0830</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAMBURG, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The weekly magazine Der Spiegel
declared Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev its ``man of the
year'' Saturday for his reform efforts at home and his contributions
to arms reductions.
   The left-leaning national magazine praised Gorbachev for
initiating bold social and economic reforms in the Soviet Union and
for working toward arms control agreements with the United States.
   The declaration was a first in the history of the magazine.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>UNIVERSAL CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jazz guitarist Larry Carlton, whose
left arm was paralyzed and voice nearly lost in a shooting by an
intruder eight months ago, returned to performing with a benefit
concert for crime victims.
   Carlton has undergone extensive physical training and voice
therapy since the April 6 random attack at his Hollywood Hills
studio. No arrests have been made in the shooting.
   ``I'm fine. I was left with this voice, and from this day
forward, this is the voice I will bring to you to say `I love you,'
'' Carlton said in a raspy voice after receiving a standing ovation
Friday night at the Universal Amphitheater.
   Carlton, 40, then performed a blues jam to show he was back in
the form that put him on more than 3,000 career recordings with such
artists as Steely Dan, Joni Mitchell and Michael Jackson, as well as
11 solo albums.
   Miss Mitchell was among those who joined Carlton on stage for the
concert to raise money for Carlton's HIP organization _ Helping
Innocent People. The group will make money available to a California
victim assistance program.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight years after the murder of John
Lennon, the younger brother of Paul McCartney is hoping his exhibit
of silkscreens and early Beatles' photographs will help uphold the
fallen Beatle's good name.
   Michael McCartney, 44, a photographer and writer of children's
books who lives in his native Liverpool, opened the exhibit
Thursday, the eighth anniversary of Lennon's death in New York City.
   ``There are few people in this world who I've been proud to meet,
and Lennon is one of them ... a lovely, charming man,'' McCartney
said. ``All you go on is what people are. You should never listen to
stories secondhand.''
   The exhibit includes photographs taken by a camera Paul McCartney
bought for his brother while performing in Hamburg, West Germany,
long before the Beatles became superstars.
   One image of Lennon at 19, laughing at his detractors after an
early Beatles' show in Liverpool, makes a good response to ``The
Lives of John Lennon,'' an unflattering biography by Albert Goldman
published this fall, McCartney said.
   ``It's disgusting that John can't do anything about this book,''
McCartney said. ``The dead can't defend themselves.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Author Clive Cussler, whose National
Underwater and Marine Agency looks for sunken ships, now is looking
for a lost train.
   Cussler, a Golden resident and author of such novels as ``Raise
the Titanic,'' is seeking volunteers to search for a Kansas-Pacific
locomotive believed buried in the dry bed of Kiowa Creek, about 30
miles east of Denver, during an 1878 flood.
   It was hauling 25 cars and a caboose when it ran off a washed-out
bridge, the marine agency said. The train's engineer, fireman and
brakeman were killed. The locomotive was never found.
   It is thought the engine may have sunk as much as 50 feet to
bedrock through quicksand stirred up by floodwaters.
   ``This locomotive was the only local history mystery we could
find,'' said Craig Dirgo, director of special projects for the
Colorado-based agency, which has specialized in looking for sunken
vessels, including the Merrimac, Titanic and the U-20 submarine,
which sank the Lusitania.
   Dirgo said Cussler will lead a group of volunteers the weekend of
Jan 7-8 to look for the engine.
   ``You just can't lose an all-metal locomotive,'' Dirgo said. He
estimated it weighed 200,000 pounds.
   Dirgo said the most recent organized search for the train was in
May 1953 by a Colorado School of Mines professor. ``They only
searched an area of 150 by 400 feet and didn't have the kind of
equipment we have now,'' Dirgo said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spanish opera star Jose Carreras charmed
critics with his talent and courage in his first full concert before
Italian fans since fighting off leukemia last year.
   Carreras, 42, performed Argentinian composer Ariel Ramirez's
``South American Creole Mass'' and ``Our Christmas,'' as well as
other popular Argentinian and Spanish pieces.
   The Rome daily Il Messaggero called the concert a ``triumph,''
saying Carreras sang with ``the passion and will to live of a man
who has fought and won a very difficult battle.''
   Proceeds of the Friday concert in a Vatican auditorium, will be
donated to the Italian Association Against Leukemia.
</TEXT>
