<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Bush-Quake     12-10 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Quake,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Calls for `Free Flow' of Aid to Quake Victims</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Quake Aid Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos WX16, WX17, WX18</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Bush called Saturday for a free
flow of aid to earthquake victims in Armenia and the Soviet
ambassador said his countrymen have been ``deeply moved'' by the
outpouring of sympathy.
   ``If something has to be changed to expedite help to the people,
it should be done,'' Bush said as he paid a condolence call at the
Soviet Embassy. ``I know of no barriers.''
   Bush and his wife, Barbara, dressed in black, were among a stream
of visitors Saturday to sign a book at the embassy and look at news
photographs of the earthquake damage in Armenia, where Soviet
officials estimate as many as 45,000 people were killed.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz came a few minutes later and
had a private discussion with Soviet Ambassador Yuri Dubinin, who
delivered a letter from Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze.
   Dubinin would not disclose the contents of the letter, and Shultz
left the embassy without saying what was in it.
   The State Department has set up an around-the-clock task force to
monitor the situation in Armenia and relay information. Two teams of
disaster relief specialists left the United States on Saturday
aboard planes that also carried supplies.
   ``This is an immense tragedy, and we are responding to is in
every way we can,'' Shultz said.
   The embassy, which has opened its iron gates to anyone wanting to
sign the book of condolences, has had to install extra telephone
lines to handle all of the calls that have been coming in since the
earthquake on Wednesday, said Soviet spokesman Boris Malakhov.
   Dubinin said, ``We are deeply moved by the response. We are open
to all assistance necessary to help people.'' At the top of the list
of items needed were medical equipment and supplies, he said.
   Robert Gale, the Los Angeles physician who helped treat victims
of the Chernobyl nuclear disaster in the Soviet Union, was among
those heading for Armenia.
   Dubinin told reporters that Gale's presence did not mean that the
earthquake had damaged nuclear facilities in the area.
   ``There is absolutely no information about any radiation
difficulties,'' he said. A nuclear power station in Armenia was
unaffected by the earthquake, he said.
   Dubinin said the response to the tragedy was part of a ``new
political spirit in the world,'' adding that people should be united
``not only in disasters.''
   The Bushes, accompanied by incoming national security adviser
Brent Scowcroft, entered the embassy through a mirrored hallway and
were escorted up a red-carpeted staircase beneath a large portrait
of Lenin, where they were greeted by Dubinin.
   Mrs. Bush kissed Liana Dubinin, the ambassador's wife, before
they entered the room where the book was kept on a red-draped table
trimmed in black. A Soviet flag topped with two black ribbons stood
in the room, where the chandeliers, paintings and mirrors all were
covered in black.
   ``With anguish in our hearts for all those in the Soviet Union
who lost loved ones,'' Bush wrote in the book.
   Representatives of other governments, including China, Britain,
Pakistan and the Vatican, came to the embassy to sign the book
around the time of the visits by Bush and Shultz.
</TEXT>
