<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     12-10 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND FORKS, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Marlan Perhus asked, ``Will you
marry me?'' Lisa Verwest was almost too frightened to answer.
   Perhus, an aviation student at the University of North Dakota,
popped the question at an altitude of 2,500 feet _ as the engine of
his Cessna 172 sputtered and coughed.
   It was an ``emergency'' Perhus said he cooked up as part of an
elaborate plan to propose to Miss Verwest, a North Dakota State
University student.
   Perhus had hidden a red-wrapped box containing a diamond ring in
the pouch behind his pilot's seat when he and Miss Verwest went for
a Sunday morning flight last month to celebrate their first
anniversary of going out.
   His flight plan was to put the plane's engine on low idle and ask
Miss Verwest to reach into the pouch for an emergency checklist, in
hopes she would find the ring instead, Perhus said.
   ``I had just reduced the power, like when you take your foot off
the accelerator in a car,'' Perhus said, which made the plane's
engine ``pop and sputter a little bit.''
   But Miss Verwest, in her nervous search for the emergency list,
missed the ring box. Perhus had to help.
   ``When she saw it, that's when I said, `Will you marry me?'''
Perhus recalled. ``After the fear subsided, she said a great big
`Yes,' with a hug, and a kiss or two.''
   ``I was basically stunned,'' Miss Verwest said.
   The couple plan to finish college before they set a wedding date.
   Perhus said after he earns his degree in aviation, he hopes to
work with the Federal Aviation Administration _ as an accident
prevention specialist.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cleanliness may be a virtue, but it's not fiscally
responsible according to a consulting firm that decided a state-run
nursing home has too many employees.
   ``I don't think I've ever seen a public building that's
cleaner,'' said Bill Evans, vice president of Cresap Management
Consultants in Washington, D.C., the company paid $200,000 to study
Colorado's social services operation.
   ``It's just spic and span. They wash the windows inside and out
once a week. We saw them mopping spotless floors _ floors that were
spotless before they were mopped.''
   While the 240-bed Trinidad State Nursing Home in southern
Colorado got high marks for cleanliness and staff care, it got a low
mark for fiscal efficiency in the presentation Evans made Wednesday
to the legislature's budget-writing committee.
   Social Services Director Irene Ibarra said Friday the cleanliness
issue was not the type of criticism she expected.
   ``That's the part I can't get over,'' she said. ``The residents
are happy with what is being done. I think that's what we should be
doing in this state. They really do a very good job down there.''
</TEXT>
