<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     12-10 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heavy Snow In The Lower Great Lakes Region</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Up to 14 inches of snow fell around parts of the eastern Great
Lakes on Saturday, and parts of New Mexico were hit by several
inches of snow.
   Squalls brought heavy snow to parts of northern and western New
York state during the night with 14 inches at Sinclairville, 12
inches at Springville and up to 8 inches south of Watertown.
   The northeastern corner of Ohio had gotten up to a foot of snow
since Friday.
   More snow was possible across the region.
   Snow fell heavily in the mountains of south-central New Mexico.
Los Lunas and Belen each received 5 inches of snow during the
morning and a winter weather advisory was posted into Sunday morning
for parts of north-central Texas.
   Snow also fell across much of Michigan, ranging from about 1 inch
at Detroit to 6 inches at Houghton on the Upper Peninsula.
   ``The best way to call it is snow-covered and slippery,'' said
Deputy Mark Bronson of the Kalamazoo County (Mich.) Sheriff's
Department. ``We have an inordinate amount of fender-benders, but I
don't think there was anything serious.''
   Light snow fell over parts of extreme northern Wisconsin.
   Showers spread rain across much of the south-central part of the
nation during the afternoon.
   Elsewhere, the Pacific Northwest had clouds and drizzle, while
fog was prevalent in the valleys of California.
   Blustery north wind pushed cold arctic air into the central and
eastern areas of the nation. Afternoon temperatures were generally
below freezing from eastern Montana through the upper half of the
Mississippi Valley to New England, with readings still below zero in
eastern North Dakota and northwestern Minnesota.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 8
degrees below zero at International Falls, Minn., to 81 at
Homestead, Fla. Saturday morning's low was 21 degrees below zero at
Warroad, Minn.
   For Sunday, light snow or snow showers were forecast across the
northern and central Plains, with show showers also expected in the
Great Lakes region. Showers were forecast from the southern high
Plains through Louisiana and southern Arkansas to the southern
Atlantic Coast.
   Highs remaining below freezing were predicted from the northern
and central Plains to the northern half of the Atlantic Coast, with
highs in the teens or single digits from eastern North Dakota and
eastern South Dakota to New England; above 50 in the lower Rio
Grande Valley of Texas and from the central Gulf Coast across
southern Georgia and northern Florida, with highs in the 60s and 70s
across the Florida Peninsula; in the 50s and 60s along most of the
Pacific Coast to southern Arizona; in the 70s in extreme southern
California; and in the 30s and 40s elsewhere.
</TEXT>
