<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Reagan-Radio     12-10 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Radio,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Says US Policies Helped Bring Soviet Changes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan on Saturday praised social
reforms and military forces cutbacks proposed by Mikhail S.
Gorbachev but said that the Soviets are keeping a big advantage in
ground troops and conventional weapons.
   ``I was encouraged by the new promises of reform that Mr.
Gorbachev made before the United Nations, and hope to see these and
past promises translated into permanent institutional changes that
will signal to the peoples of the Soviet Union and the world a
courageous commitment to a new path of democratization,'' Reagan
said in his weekend radio address.
   Reagan lauded Gorbachev for his proposed reforms and attempts to
open Soviet society, saying, ``If this vision is realized and these
promises are turned into deeds, we would be witnessing a dramatic
change in the Soviet system.''
   The Soviet president, in an address to the U.N. General Assembly,
pledged to slash Soviet troop strength by 500,000 men, and 10,000
tanks within two years. He offered to withdraw six tank divisions
from East Germany, Czechoslovakia and Hungary by 1991, and to reduce
Soviet forces in those countries by 50,000 men and 5,000 tanks.
   ``These unilateral reductions ... would give a long-awaited
encouragement to our efforts to achieve the genuine balance in
conventional forces that would assure greater security and greater
stability in Western Europe,'' Reagan said.
   In his five-minute talk, delivered from the Camp David retreat in
the Catoctin Mountains outside Washington, Reagan maintained the
upbeat tone he's set since concluding his final meeting with
Gorbachev on Wednesday in New York.
   ``We welcome the Soviet force reductions that are promised, but
let's remember this: even after these redeployments are completed in
1991, the Warsaw Pact will still have a large conventional advantage
an edge of about five-to-two in tanks and artillery and some 300,000
more troops,'' he said.
   The president took some credit for helping bring these changes
about, saying: ``Our steadfastness, our policies, our whole approach
has borne fruit.
   ``We have not come this way through lack of strength or any
weakness in our resolve, nor has there been anything inevitable out
what we've achieved.
   ``The unity, confidence, power and firmness of the democracies
has brought us forward and maintaining this firm alliance will keep
us moving forward.''
</TEXT>
