<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Jordan-Palestine     12-10 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jordan-Palestine,0521</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rallies to mark Palestinian uprising disrupted by clashes.
^Eds: Atallah Atallah in 12th graf is cq</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rallies to mark the first anniversary of the
Palestinian uprising in the Israeli-occupied territories collapsed
in brawling and confusion Saturday.
   The head of Jordan's professional associations accused government
agencies of provoking the disruptions.
   A planned noon march at the University of Jordan by pro-PLO
supporters ended in stone-throwing, club-swinging battles with
Jordanian nationalists who ripped up pictures of Palestine
Liberation Organization chairman Yasser Arafat.
   Reporters saw at least one person injured, but there was no
official report on the number of casualties.
   In the evening, the Professional Associations' Union canceled a
series of events scheduled to commemorate the anniversary of the
uprising in the West Bank and Gaza Strip after a Jordanian-based
Palestinian dissident group disrupted a scheduled lecture.
   ``These people are sent by the government because they want to
stop our activities,'' said Laith Shubeilat, head of the council of
11 associations that represent most of the country's doctors,
nurses, engineers, lawyers, journalists and other professionals.
   ``These hired hands and hired voices under the protection of the
government interfered, uninvited, on the premises,'' Shubeilat told
The Associated Press.
   An estimated 1.5 million Palestinians live in Jordan, most of
them in the capital, Amman.
   Most fled from Palestine after Israel was created as a state in
1948 and when Israel occupied the West Bank and Gaza Strip during
the 1967 Middle East War.
   At the university, reporters saw about 100 students chanting
slogans in favor of King Hussein and throwing rocks at about the
same number of students gathering to start a march to mark the
uprising anniversary.
   After retreating into the Engineering Association building, some
of the pro-PLO students emerged and battled the Jordanian
nationalists before security forces stopped the fighting.
   On Thursday, a Palestinian faction led by PLO dissident Atallah
Atallah packed a conference hall hours before the start of planned
lectures sponsored by the Professional Associations' Union and then
interrupted the speakers and clashed with Arafat supporters.
   About 200 of Atallah's followers arrived early Saturday for a
scheduled poetry reading in honor of the uprising, and Shubeilat
said the association canceled the event to avoid disturbances.
   He said folklore and musical programs planned for Sunday and
Monday also were canceled.
   Atallah opposes Arafat's leadership of the PLO and favors strong
ties with Jordan, which has granted his organization unusual freedom
of action. He denies PLO allegations he is backed by Jordan.
   Jordan has been under martial law since the 1967 war.
   Public demonstrations are rarely permitted, and Hussein's
government is wary of expressions of Palestinian nationalism since a
1970 war with Palestinian guerrillas that drove thousands of
Palestinian refugees into Lebanon.
   Hussein renounced sovereignty over the West Bank July 31,
formally giving the PLO responsibility for the area. He declared
that ``Jordan is not Palestine'' and called for Jordanian citizens
to honor their duties to their own country.
 
</TEXT>
