<1ST_LINE>r p AM-ChicagoMayoral     12-10 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chicago Mayoral,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Daley And Jackson Top New Poll, But Jesse's Not A Candidate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cook County State's Attorney Richard M. Daley
leads in the race for mayor, and presidential hopeful Jesse Jackson
_ who isn't even in the running _ would be his toughest competitor,
a poll has found.
   Daley, son of the the late Mayor Richard J. Daley, would garner
52 percent of the vote while fellow Democrat Jackson would get 40
percent in a one-on-one race, according to the poll published in
Sunday editions of the Chicago Tribune.
   Voters polled also favored Daley over Mayor Eugene Sawyer and
Alderman Timothy Evans _ both black and considered strong contenders
_ and gave him the most favorable rating of the top five Democratic
candidates.
   Half of all blacks polled said no black candidate measures up to
former Mayor Harold Washington, whose death in November 1987 created
the need for the special election April 4. The Democratic primary is
set for Feb. 28. Only one Republican has announced his candidacy in
the largely Democratic city.
   The telephone poll of 1,038 registered Chicago voters found that
Sawyer and Evans both lack the broad support needed to re-create the
multiracial coalition that won the mayor's office twice for
Washington, the city's first black mayor. The city's population is
40 percent black.
   Jackson would have the best chance of regrouping the Washington
forces and beating Daley in a one-on-one confrontation, the poll
found.
   Asked opinions of candidates or possible candidates, 55 percent
of those polled gave Jackson, a civil rights leader and former
presidential candidate, a favorable rating. Daley was viewed
favorably by 59 percent, Sawyer by 43 percent and Evans by 39
percent.
   Jackson ``is not a candidate'' and won't comment on the poll,
press secretary Eric Easter said Saturday.
   Daley does not expect Jackson to enter the race, but ``obviously
if he (Jackson) were to run he'd be a strong candidate,'' said David
Wilhelm, Daley's campaign manager.
   The poll was conducted Dec. 2-5 by Market Shares Corp. of
suburban Mount Prospect and has an error margin of plus or minus 3
percent.
   In a two-way race against Sawyer, who is set to announce his
candidacy officially Sunday, Daley was favored by 59 percent
compared to 30 percent for the acting mayor. In a race with Evans,
Daley would win 56 percent to 34 percent, the poll found.
   Of blacks polled, 45 percent favored Sawyer over Daley, and 62
percent favored Evans over Daley.
</TEXT>
