<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Streisand     12-10 0192</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Streisand,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Streisand Pays $363,000 For Furniture By Craftsman Gustav Stickley</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barbra Streisand paid a record $363,000 Saturday
for an oak and wrought iron sideboard made by craftsman Gustav
Stickley, the top lot in an auction that brought in more than $1.9
million, Christie's auction house said.
   Streisand's telephone bid on the 1903 sideboard set a record for
a Stickley piece and for a single piece of American Arts and Crafts
movement furniture, said Christie's spokeswoman Dana Micucci. Before
the auction, its value was estimated at $90,000.
   The sideboard had been in Stickley's home in Syracuse, N.Y.,
before the designer's grandson, Peter Wiles Sr., put it up for
auction along with several other pieces from the house. Streisand
bought three other Stickley items and two Frank Lloyd Wright
drawings at the auction, said Micucci.
   A Stickley oak directors table sold to an unidentified New York
dealer for $121,000, and an inlaid oak piano and bench created by
Stickley and Harvey Ellis sold for $77,000, she said.
   Stickley, who died in 1942, is regarded as one of the leaders in
the field of American Arts and Crafts furniture.
</TEXT>
