<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ComaBirth     12-10 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Coma Birth,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Comatose Woman Gives Birth after Rare Medical Procedure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who has been in a coma for more than five
months gave birth to a healthy boy by Caesarian section after labor
was induced in a rarely used procedure, officials said Saturday.
   The 8-pound, one-half-ounce baby was delivered to Barbara
Blodgett, 24, of Yakima without complication late Friday, said Kay
Rodriguez of University Hospital.
   The mother, injured in a June 30 car wreck when she was three
months pregnant, was listed in satisfactory condition.
   David Blodgett, who escaped serious injury in the accident,
attended his wife during delivery, Rodriguez said. The couple met
while serving on a U.S. Forest Service firefighting crew, and
co-workers later donated vacation time so Blodgett could remain with
his wife.
   ``Her prognosis for recovery (from brain stem injuries) is very
guarded,'' said L.G. Blanchard, another hospital spokesman.
Blanchard said she was being fed intravenously but was breathing on
her own.
   Dr. Thomas Benedetti, a University of Washington medical
professor as well as Mrs. Blodgett's physician, said the induction
of labor in a comatose woman was relatively rare.
   Doctors used drugs to put the woman in labor after determining
that the baby's lungs were sufficiently developed. After five hours
of labor, however, it was clear the baby was too big for a regular
delivery so Caesarean surgery was performed, Rodriguez said.
   The accident killed Mrs. Blodgett's cousin, Nicole Valenzuela.
The driver of the other car, Byron Stackhouse, 37, was convicted of
vehicular assault after admitting he had been drinking before the
wreck. He faces a maximum sentence of five years in prison and a
$10,000 fine.
</TEXT>
