<FILEID>AP-NR-12-10-88 1824EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Czechoslovakia     12-10 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Czechoslovakia,0552</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Attend Rally To Demand More Freedom</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An estimated 3,000 people Saturday
demonstrated for more freedom in the first independent rally
permitted by Communist authorities in nearly 20 years.
   Dissidents who were detained to prevent their attendance at
banned demonstrations in August and October were cheered by the
crowd as they spoke at the rally.
   But former Communist Party leader Alexander Dubcek, who was
ousted after his reform program was crushed by a Soviet-led invasion
in 1968, was placed under virtual house arrest Friday in Bratislava
when French President Francois Mitterrand Mitterrand visited that
city.
   Dubcek told reporters police cars circled his residence in
Bratislava Friday when Mitterrand, a socialist, was in the city and
he could not leave his home. His wife, Anna, said the police patrols
were removed Saturday.
   Mitterrand, during his two-day visit to Czechoslovakia that ended
Friday, praised Dubcek's attempted reforms that became known as the
``Prague Spring.''
   At Saturday's rally the crowd chanted ``Freedom!'' ``Release
political prisoners'' and ``Long live Charter 77'' during an hour of
speeches by activists from the Charter 77 human rights movement and
other dissident groups.
   The rally, called to mark the 40th anniversary of the 1948
Declaration of Human Rights, had been scheduled for Prague's
Wenceslas Square. Authorities barred the gathering in the city
center but approved of another site about a mile away.
   After the speeches the crowd shouted approval of resolutions,
including publication of the human rights declaration and other
human rights pacts in school texts, public participation in the
preparation of a new constitution, and negotiations with the
nation's churches for full religious freedom.
   It was the first time since January 1969 that the Communist
authorities had permitted a rally by independent groups.
   Banned playwright Vaclav Havel was the first to address the crowd.
   ``Three weeks ago, when I was in (Prague's) Ruzyne prison,
wondering how long I would be there, if anybody told me that I would
be having breakfast with the French president and the next day
addressing a permitted meeting, I would have said he was joking,''
he said.
   He said Saturday's rally would not have been possible without the
``brave participation'' of thousands of people in the August and
October demonstrations, which were broken up by police.
   Havel said he did not know if the permission for the rally marked
a major change by the authorities, but he said, ``One thing is
certain, the situation is open and it is up to us all how it is
going to develop.''
   Havel was one of eight dissidents who met with Mitterrand Friday
to discuss human rights.
   A government-sponsored forum on human rights also was held
Saturday at at an exhibition hall in a Prague park.
   The delegates approved the creation of committee on human affairs
that speakers said would improve laws on health and social affairs
and guarantee existing laws are not violated.
   But the organizers did not admit three dissidents who tried to
attend the forum.
   ``There are no rights and freedoms without the duty not to exceed
the determined borders,'' said keynote speaker Josef Mecl, dean of
the law faculty at Prague's Charles University.
</TEXT>
