<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Laos-USMIAS     12-10 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Laos-US MIAS,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S.-Laos Mission Excavating Wartime Crash Site</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A team of U.S. experts flew to Laos on
Saturday to find out what happened to an American pilot whose
single-seat reconnaissance aircraft went down during a March 1968
wartime mission.
   The excavation in the southern Laotian province of Savannakhet
will take about 10 days and involve 16 Americans and a number of
Laotian counterparts, said Lt. Col. Thomas J. Boyd, a spokesman for
the U.S. Pacific Command.
   The fourth joint excavation in Laos is part of an operation aimed
at resolving the fates of 547 U.S. servicemen still listed as
missing in action in the communist nation. The U.S. Department of
Defense also lists 1,747 MIAs in Vietnam, 83 in Cambodia and six in
China from the long war in Indochina.
   Boyd said the excavation was the result of a joint survey of the
Sepone area undertaken by U.S.-Laotian personnel in late September
and early October.
   Boyd said two U.S. C-130s flew the team Friday from Clark Air
Force Base in the Philippines to Bangkok. The aircraft flew on to
Vientiane, the capital of Laos, where the team was to be transported
to the remote crash site by helicopters.
   He said the team included explosive and ordnance experts, a
physician and a U.S. State Department official. Most of the team
members come from the Hawaii-based Joint Casualty Resolution Center
and Central Identification Laboratory, the units charged with
resolving the MIA issue.
   The three earlier joint investigations found no remains of U.S.
servicemen, but Boyd said the Laotians in February turned over
remains they said were found in searches of two sites in which
Americans did not participate.
   Boyd said an investigation to determine whether the remains were
those of Americans was continuing.
</TEXT>
