<DOCNO> AP881210-0125 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-10-88 1840EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-OrbisonMemorials     12-10 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Orbison Memorials,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Memorials in Two Cities for Roy Orbison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Friends of popular music legend Roy
Orbison say memorial services will be held in Nashville and in Los
Angeles for the singer, who died last week of a heart attack.
   A public prayer service, organized by Grand Ole Opry star Jean
Shepard, is planned for Sunday afternoon at College Heights Baptist
Church in Nashville.
   Orbison, known for such hits as ``Blue Bayou'' and ``Only the
Lonely,'' died Tuesday in suburban Hendersonville at age 52. He had
lived in or near Nashville for 30 years until moving to California
three years ago.
   ``We just felt the need to get together and pray for him,'' Ms.
Shepard said Friday. ``Good friends are hard to come by and Roy was
a good friend.''
   She said the event was intended to be for Nashville musicians who
have worked with Orbison, but fans would not be turned away.
   ``It would be OK, I'm sure. Roy belonged to the people,'' she
said.
   In Los Angeles, a family spokesman, Greg Thompson of Sarah
McMullen Public Relations, said Orbison's burial would be closed to
the public.
   Also expected to be private is a gathering Tuesday at a Los
Angeles nightspot for Orbison's family and friends on the West
Coast, Thompson said. But a public memorial may be held later, he
said.
</TEXT>
