<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AirlineFares     12-10 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airline Fares,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>United Introduces New Business Discount Fare</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Airlines, which curtailed its cut-rate
fares just two weeks ago along with other carriers, added a discount
fare Saturday it said is aimed at the ``price-sensitive business
traveler.''
   The fare requires that travelers buy their tickets seven days in
advance. A 25 percent penalty will be assessed for canceling
reservations.
   The fare level, which went into effect Saturday, is lower than
the increased prices most U.S. airlines put into effect last month
for persons buying tickets a few days before their flights. But the
fare is still ``significantly higher'' than rates before the price
rise, Rob Doughty, a United spokesman, said Friday.
   ``There was a segment of the market that wasn't being addressed
by the new fares, but fares have to go up,'' he said. ``This was an
attempt to mesh those two needs.''
   United's non-stop one-way fare between Chicago and Los Angeles,
for example, drops from $525 to $362 with the new discount, compared
with $239 under the discount eliminated last month. The fare between
Denver and Los Angeles decreases from $320 to $272, compared with
$230 under the old discount fare.
   Although the price increases did not result in a decline in
traffic in the last two weeks, United was ``concerned that in the
long term we could see some impact,'' Doughty said.
   He predicted other carriers would follow United's changes.
</TEXT>
