<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Quake-Survivors     12-10 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quake-Survivors,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Doctors Wage 24-Hour Struggle to Save Survivors</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YEREVAN, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alla Pogosyan and her niece heard a
noise from a the fourth-floor of an apartment house, and the
building began to shake.
   ``I couldn't open the door,'' she recalled Saturday from a bed in
the hall of a hospital in Yerevan, capital of Armenia. ``I put up my
hand, and somebody took it.''
   She was no longer near the top of the five-story building in the
Armenian city of Stepanavan. She was near the top of a pile of
rubble in a devastated community.
   Unlike many others in similar buildings that Wednesday morning,
she survived an earthquake that devastated northwestern Armenia.
Tens of thousands were killed, but countless survivors were trapped
in the rubble. A half million people were estimated to be homeless.
   Ms. Pogosyan still doesn't know what happened to her niece.
   Another survivor at the Yerevan Surgical Institute, 9-year-old
Violetta Saliksyan, lay motionless in her bed, her bruised face
turned toward a weeping relative.
   She was home with her mother, father, grandfather and sister in
the Armenian city of Leninakan when the quake struck. Her mother and
grandmother died, and the rest of the family is now in three
hospitals.
   Five-hundred of the most seriously injured have been sent to the
Yerevan Institute.
   In its first official estimate, the government estimated Saturday
that 12,000 people were injured.
   Gradually, their relatives are finding them. At this hospital,
they are guided by typewritten lists of patients posted on the brick
walls outside.
   ``The entire staff since the seventh has not left the
institution, not a cleaning lady, not a doctor has left,'' said the
hospital's director, Alexander Mikhailyan.
   So far, 18 patients have died there, he said.
   But doctors are waging a battle against what they call ``crush
syndrome'' _ permanent physical damage from the pressure of huge
slabs of concrete and other debris.
   Chief surgeon Ruben Ovanasyan said crush syndrome has caused 14
of the 18 deaths. that.
   Doctors say they need more artificial kidney machines and
blood-filtering devices to save the seriously ill. Of the hospital's
500 patients, 48 are using its three kidney machines, seriously
overtaxing their capacity.
   Mikhailyan said 79 new patients were brought to the hospital
Saturday, mostly transferred from other hospitals. Meanwhile, it
sent 35 patients to a Yerevan cancer hospital and 31 to Moscow.
   ``We haven't seen this kind of situation in our halls,'' said
Mikhailyan. Hour by hour, green military helicopters buzzed almost
constantly overhead bringing more of the dead and injured to the
capital.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
