<HEAD>Radio Kabul Reports 24 Killed In Air Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fighter jets bombed the southern
Afghan city of Kandahar this week and killed 24 people, Afghanistan
government radio reported Saturday.
   Radio Kabul, monitored in Islambad, did not say who the planes in
Thursday's attack belonged to. It said the bombers flew in from the
east, presumably from the direction of Pakistan.
   The radio provided sketchy details. It said the raid injured
eight people and damaged 10 houses. A military unit was also hit,
and eight soldiers and an officer were injured, it said.
   Radio Kabul also reported a car bomb exploded in the Afghan
capital Kabul early Saturday, injuring dozens of people with broken
glass from shattered windows.
   Kandahar, the ancient capital of Afghanistan, has been under
siege for several months by Moslem guerrillas fighting the
Soviet-backed government.
   Western diplomats, independent witness reports and guerrilla
sources reported seeing Soviet-made MiG-27 jets bombing guerrillas
positions around the city in late October and early November.
   Islamabad and Kabul have been trading charges of interference and
accord violations almost since the signing in April.
   Pakistan has denied repeated charges of armed interference in
Afghanistan levelled by the communist government in Kabul. The
United States and Pakistan support Moslem insurgents, who have been
fighting the Kabul government for the past 10 years.
   An agreement signed in April provides for the withdrawal of an
estimated 100,000 Soviet soldiers from Afghanistan.
   Pakistan and Afghanistan signed the U.N.-brokered agreement,
which was co-guaranteed by Moscow and Washington.
</TEXT>
