<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AbortionProtests     12-10 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Abortion Protests,0493</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protesters Arrested Outside Abortion Clinic In Three States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested more than 500 people at anti-abortion protests
Saturday in California, Texas and Ohio as demonstrators sang hymns
and Christmas carols, drew hecklers and forced authorities to drag
them into custody.
   Almost 400 protesters were arrested outside Planned Parenthood
clinics in the Northern California communities of Concord and
Fairfield, police said.
   Police in Austin, Texas, arrested 85 people during a
demonstration outside The Ladies Center clinic, where abortions are
performed. Most of the protesters went limp, forcing officers to
carry them into three vans and a bus, a process that took more than
three hours in a chilly rain.
   In Columbus, Ohio, police arrested 52 anti-abortion activists as
they attempted to barricade the entrance to the Founders Clinic near
downtown.
   The anti-abortion protesters all were associated with Operation
Rescue, a group that has organized such demonstrations nationwide
and with particular impact in Atlanta during and since the
Democratic National Convention in July.
   Terri Conklin, a director of the Project Rescue spinoff group in
Ohio, said trained counselors were at the Columbus protest to advise
any women seeking abortions to go to ``pregnancy distress centers''
where, if they decided against abortion, they would be provided with
baby clothes and furniture.
   Columbus police said most of those arrested were charged with
disorderly conduct and resisting arrest and taken to the county
jail. About half of the protesters passively resisted arrest by
refusing to walk and had to be carried to a police van.
   In Concord, Calif., police Lt. Bob Burns said 184 people there
were cited for trespassing on private property and released.
   Kelly Connelly of Operation Rescue said about 320 anti-abortion
participants drew about 75 pro-choice protesters in Concord.
   ``They were making a lot of noise and kind of harrassing the
`rescuers,''' said Burns. But police said none of the
counter-demonstrators were arrested.
   ``It was all very gentlemanly,'' said Burns.
   Fairfield Police Lt. Jerry Shepard said 215 people were arrested,
processed and released at a similar demonstration involving close to
400 people at a Planned Parenthood clinic there.
   In Austin, Lt. David Balagia said police expected to file
criminal trespass charges against most of the protesters arrested
Saturday. There were also arrests in Austin on Friday, when 34
people were charged with criminal trespass after they blocked the
entrances to two clinics.
   Rex Moses, a spokesman for the organizing group Austin Rescue and
one of those arrested Saturday, said he was proud of the protesters
arrested in Friday's actions, but added that he did not want to
``gloat'' in front of police.
   The Texas Abortion Rights Action League said the four protests
staged by Austin Rescue since October cost the city $29,000 in
police overtime expenses. The clinic had three abortions scheduled
for Saturday, and all were rescheduled, said league executive
director Phyllis Dunham.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
