<1ST_LINE>u a AM-HighwayKillings 2ndLd-Writethru a0603 12-10 0782</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Highway Killings, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0603,0798</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Bedford Strugges With Serial Killings</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs grafs 11-12, `In nearby...' to UPDATE with details of
finding of sixth body, CORRECT name of highway to Interstate 195
sted Route 195. Picks up 13th graf pvs, `The killings...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW BEDFORD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tourists can walk cobblestone streets
and see buildings standing since this seaport's whaling days, but
the slayings of at least five women this year have focused
outsiders' attention on seedy Weld Square.
   Five bodies of women have been found dumped along highways since
July, and three have been identified and linked to the square, an
area known for drugs and prostitution a few blocks from the historic
section.
   Saturday, skeletal remains of a sixth body were found in the
area, but police did not immediately determine whether they were
part of the string of killings.
   Police said at least one of the women whose bodies were found
earlier was strangled. The victims' skeletal remains have been sent
to the FBI for examination.
   While dozens of investigators comb the region for more bodies and
for any suspects, prostitutes still walk the streets of Weld Square
day and night.
   ``I'm worried, yeah, but I've got to make a living,'' said one
woman who said she was a prostitute and declined to give her name.
   Mayor John Bullard said the killings have not frightened most
townspeople.
   ``The people who have reason to be terrified are the prostitutes.
But that is a very small, very identifiable problem,'' Bullard said.
``There is no reason for people who are not prostitutes to feel
threatened by this.''
   In fact, the mayor said he is more concerned with the city's drug
problem.
   ``The biggest problem is the waste of human lives that takes
place off the front pages,'' Bullard said. ``That's a much greater
impact than five people having their lives taken.''
   In nearby Dartmouth, police said that skeletal remains located
Saturday were found by hunters in a gravel pit about a quarter-mile
into the woods off Interstate 195. The other five bodies found since
July were within 25 feet of the interstate or Route 140 in Dartmouth
and Freetown.
   Neither the body's sex nor the cause of death could be
immediately determined, authorities said. Police gave no indication
they had any evidence other than proximity to link the body to the
five slayings.
   The killings have added a new chapter to the town's troubled
history.
   A city of highs and lows, New Bedford was once the whaling
capital of the world. That industry rapidly collapsed and textile
manufacturing swiftly took its place. Then the mills migrated south
toward cheaper labor earlier this century, leaving an economic wound
in New Bedford that has only recently begun to heal.
   Today, despite higher-than-average unemployment and a polluted
harbor, this city of 98,000 about 50 miles south of Boston boasts
the nation's richest fishing port in the dollar value of its catch.
   But more people remember the city for the 1983 gang rape of a
woman on a pool table at a bar called Big Dan's in the city's
scruffy South End. The case resulted in four convictions and
national television and newspaper coverage.
   Earlier this summer, as the first bodies in the murder case were
discovered in dense woods near two highways, a movie based on the
Big Dan's case drew protests from some residents.
   Efforts to improve New Bedford and its image have taken many
forms.
   The New Bedford Whaling museum is famous across the country. The
mayor is trying to bring a state park to the city. The downtown area
has preserved its appearance and one can walk for blocks on
cobblestone streets among whaling-era buildings.
   Not far from downtown, Joe Thomas works on a periodical devoted
to New Bedford's history. It is called ``Spinners,'' after the
millworkers who flocked to the city at the turn of the century. He
said he worries about problems more permanent than the series of
murders.
   ``I am concerned with the way people see themselves. I don't care
what other people think,'' Thomas said. He said New Bedford ``has a
pretty low wage level; it's got a pretty low housing level; it's got
a pretty low education level.''
   James Mathes, executive vice president of the New Bedford Area
Chamber of Commerce, said the city will be able to recover from the
latest round of bad news by ``going out and telling people that this
is a nice community.''
   ``Murder is clearly a terrible thing. It happens throughout the
United States,'' he said. ``But when you have something this wacky,
that happens multiple times, it just hurts.''
</TEXT>
