<DOCNO> AP881210-0136 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-10-88 2054EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mexico-Drugs     12-10 0609</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Drugs,0630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Delegation Encouraged By New Mexican Government's Attitude</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mexican president Carlos Salinas de Gortari
promised visiting U.S. congressmen that he will make life miserable
for drug traffickers in Mexico, the lawmakers said Saturday.
   The congressmen said they were optimistic about the new Mexican
administration's attitude toward the battle against drugs after a
40-minute meeting with Salinas on Friday.
   The 14 lawmakers, members of the House Select Committee on
Narcotics Abuse and Control, are on a 12-day fact-finding trip to
Mexico and other nations in the Caribbean basin.
   Two years ago, on a similar fact-finding trip, committee chairman
Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., said he was disappointed by what he
perceived as lack of cooperation by Mexican officials.
   Salinas, who took office Dec. 1, told the congressmen he was
reorganizing the office of the attorney general with a special
narcotics enforcement division and planned to implement stiffer
criminal penalties and increase seizure of assets of drug dealers.
   ``I will make life miserable for drug traffickers in Mexico,
before they make life in Mexico miserable,'' the congressmen quoted
Salinas as saying.
   The congressmen said Salinas gave no specifics about how he
planned to step up the fight against official corruption or any
details of the use of seizure laws.
   Mexico has in the past expressed discontent with U.S. drug
policies, saying that they lean too much toward enforcement and that
Mexico cannot be blamed for the tremendous demand for drugs that
creates a market in the United States.
   Rangel said U.S. policy has recently shifted to an emphasis on
education, treatment and rehabilitation, rather than simply
enforcement.
   ``We have an upbeat attitude as to looking forward to the new
relationship betwen our presidents and our congresses,'' said Rangel.
   Rep. William J. Hughes, D-N.J., said Mexican authorities
expressed interest in reviewing U.S. statutes on money laundering
and bank privacy, but he did not know how they planned to use the
information.
   ``We've made errors and mistakes and we hope Mexico can benefit
from them,'' said Rep. Frank J. Guarini, D-N.J.
   Salinas said he personally intervened to press an investigation
into the killing of U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration agent
Enrique Camarena Salazar, said Rep. Mike Oxley, R-Ohio.
   Oxley said he told Salinas that a speedy resolution of the
Camarena case ``would send a positive signal'' about the Mexican
attitude on drug trafficking.
   Camarena was killed in 1985 while investigating Rafael Caro
Quintero, allegedly one of Mexico's top drug barons.
   A Mexican drug trafficker, Rene Verdugo Urquidez, was convicted
in Los Angeles and sentenced to 240 years in prison in the case in
October. His attorneys argued that he was a scapegoat.
   Caro Quintero has been sentenced to 34 years in prison in Mexico
on narcotics and weapons charges stemming from the case.
   Several other people, including Mexican police officials, have
been convicted in the case. U.S. authorities have accused Mexico of
foot-dragging in the investigation, causing strains in U.S.-Mexican
relations.
   The next stop on the delegation's tour is Belize, just south of
Mexico. The delegation's itinerary after that is not yet set,
committee staff members said.
   Committee staffer Rich Baum refused to comment on reports the
delegation is going to Cuba, but he said the island was of interest
because of its strategic location between the United States and
drug-producing areas in South America.
   He said the United States had tracked drug-carrying planes and
ships that appeared to originate in Cuba.
   Cuban President Fidel Castro last week rejected accusations that
Cuba was serving as a drug transshipment point and said that his
nation was the most drug-free nation in the Western Hemisphere.
</TEXT>
