<2ND_LINE>AM-North-Nir,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Two Planned To Acquire Soviet Tank</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former national security aide Oliver North and
the late Amiram Nir had planned to acquire a highly sophisticated
Soviet tank in Syria and have it shipped to the United States, a
published report said Saturday.
   U.S. News & World Report, quoting unnamed intelligence sources
and referring to North's still secret notebooks, called for Israel
to send an Arabic speaking arms expert with a fake Syrian passport
into that country with the help of ``unnamed Polish confederates.''
   The goal of the expedition was an advanced version of the Soviet
Union's T-72 high-tech battle tank, the magazine said in its
``Washington Whispers'' column. The plan, in which the tank would be
shipped to the United States ``via a circuitous route,'' was aborted
because of disclosure of the Iran-Contra affair in November 1986,
the magazine said.
   Nir, a former Israeli counterterrorism official, died Nov. 30 in
a plane crash in Mexico.
