<DOCNO> AP881210-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-10-88 2116EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-HumanRights 4thLd-Writethru a0589 12-10 0859</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Human Rights, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0589,0880</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sakharov And Walesa Meet On Day Dedicated To Human Rights</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with demonstration in
Czechoslovakia. Pick up 4th pvs `Walesa, leader...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PAR4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lech Walesa and Andrei Sakharov met for the first
time Saturday and discussed human rights problems in their homelands
and the reforms they believed are needed to correct them, an adviser
to Walesa said.
   The two men, both making their first foreign trip since each won
the Nobel Peace Prize, also attended ceremonies marking the 40th
anniversary of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights.
   Elsewhere Saturday, police clashed with demonstrators calling for
human rights in Tibet and Paraguay, and the leaders of nations such
as Cyprus and the Philippines issued statements calling for an end
to human rights abuses.
   In Prague, Czechoslovakia, an estimated 3,000 people demonstrated
for more freedom in the first independent rally permitted by
Communist authorities in nearly 20 years. They chanted slogans and
heard an hour of speeches by activists from the Charter 77 human
rights movement and other dissident groups.
   Walesa, leader of Poland's banned Solidarity labor movement, and
Sakharov, the Soviet human rights activist, met privately at their
hotel for about 45 minutes Saturday morning in a ``very friendly and
very warm'' session, according to Bronislaw Gemerek, an adviser to
Walesa who is acting as translator.
   ``Walesa spoke of the problems in Poland. Sakharov spoke of the
problems in the Soviet Union, and Walesa said he thinks
`perestroika' is a good program for both countries,'' said Gemerek,
speaking in French to reporters.
   Perestroika is the word used to describe Soviet President Mikhail
S. Gorbachev's program of political or economic restructuring.
   Neither Walesa nor Sakharov commented publicly on their meeting
Saturday. But Gemerek later described the encounter in detail in an
interview with The Associated Press.
   Sakharov told Walesa that ``the immense difference between the
Russian and Polish societies is that Polish society wants reform,
while in the Soviet Union people fear it,'' Gemerek said.
   ``Walesa emphasized to Sakharov that the main problem is the
democratization of the system. When you have mass support, you can
have reform. Without the democraticization of the old Stalinist
system, Gorbachev's policies ... will always be vulnerable.''
   Gemerek said Solidarity planned to step up contacts with
independent Soviet movements and activists. He also said Walesa and
Sakharov hoped to meet again during the weekend.
   Walesa and Sakharov also met separately with Premier Michel
Rocard at his Left Bank office on Saturday.
   About 1,000 people packed the great hall Saturday night at the
Palais de Chaillot, which looks across the Seine River to the Eiffel
Tower. They heard the global pledge to protect human rights that was
signed 40 years ago.
   U.N. Secretary General Javier-Perez de Cuellar and Director
General Federico Mayor of the U.N. Educational, Scientific, and
Cultural Organization made speeches. The audience included Eli
Weisel, another Nobel Peace Prize winner; Foreign Minister Hans
Dietrich Genscher of West Germany; and Hortense Allende, widow of
slain President Salvador Allende of Chile.
   In his address, French President Francois Mitterrand stressed the
importance of the free flow of information in assuring liberty.
   ``Oppression is nourished by silence,'' he said. ``Free
information is a weapon in our hands.''
   The Paris trip was the first time Walesa has been allowed to
leave Poland since authorities crushed Solidarity during martial law
in 1981 and outlawed it in 1982. He won the Nobel Peace Prize in
1983 following the creation of Solidarity, the first independent
trade federation in a communist state.
   Sakharov, who won the Nobel Peace Prize in 1975, came to Paris
after a four-week visit to the United States.
   Sakharov, a nuclear physicist who played a key role in developing
the Soviet hydrogen bomb, previously was barred from traveling
abroad because the Soviets said his scientific work gave him
knowledge of state secrets.
   For seven years, he was also restricted to the closed city of
Gorky because of his outspoken opposition to Soviet intervention in
Afghanistan.
   But in 1986, Gorbachev called him back to Moscow. Since then,
Sakharov has generally supported Gorbachev's reforms, while speaking
out against some trends, including the growing concentration of
power in Gorbachev's hands.
   The Universal Declaration of Human Rights, adopted by the U.N.
General Assembly on Dec. 10, 1948, is the basic document under which
U.N. member nations pledge to safeguard life and liberty and abolish
torture and slavery.
   In Asuncion, Paraguay, police attacked hundreds of people with
electric prods and rubber batons Saturday to prevent them from
holding a march to commemorate the the human rights anniversary.
   Several dozen people were reported injured when police charged
demonstrators and people shopping in downtown Asuncion. The
government banned the march, saying it was organized by
anti-government activists.
   Also Saturday, Chinese troops fired on Tibetan demonstrators
marking the annniversary in Lhasa, the capital of Tibet. Western
travelers said they believed two people were killed and three
wounded.
   In the Philippines, President Corazon Aquino vowed Saturday to
punish human rights violators in the military, saying soldiers who
abuse prisoners are capable of plotting coups against her.
</TEXT>
