<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Boardwalk-Fire 1stLd-Writethru a0592 12-10 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Boardwalk-Fire, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0592,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire At Atlantic City Boardwalk Destroys Much Of Amusement Park</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with fire under control, quotes from
scene, background on pier; Coleen is cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire destroyed a closed amusement
park on a Boardwalk pier and a row of seaside businesses Saturday
and briefly threatened a casino hotel before being brought under
control, authorities said.
   ``It looks like the whole thing is up (in flames), all the
amusements, all the gaming houses,'' said fire Deputy Chief Lincoln
Harold. ``When this fire gets done running its course, there won't
be hardly anything left on the pier.''
   The Resorts International Casino Hotel, which owns the pier and
is located about 75 feet away, was never close to catching fire,
officials said. However, firefighters began their assault on the
flames at the hotel to ensure they would not spread in the hotel's
direction.
   The four-alarm blaze broke out at the Steeple Chase Pier
amusement park at Pennsylvania Avenue and the Boardwalk about 11:40
a.m. It was brought under control by midevening but was expected to
continue smoldering into the night.
   One firefighter was treated at a local hospital for a knee injury
and released, authorities said.
   A fast-food restaurant was destroyed, along with a row of
abandoned restaurants and arcades on the pier.
   Coleen O'Donnell, manager of Popeye's Fried Chicken, said that
she noticed flames coming up from the building's footing about 11:45
a.m.
   ``It came from outside the building,'' she said. ``We smelled it
and we looked and we saw it coming from the bottom of the walls.''
She said that she and about eight other people in the building
``went right out the front door.''
   The cause of the fire had not been determined, Harold said.
   More than 125 firefighters, five fire engines and two trucks
battled the blaze, which was largely confined to on the
100-foot-wide, 120-foot-long pier, which is surrounded on three
sides by water and the beach.
   Harold said problems getting water out to the pier and wind
helped the fire spread initially and slowed efforts to control it.
Late Saturday, freezing temperatures hampered firefighters.
   The Trump Air helicopter pad at the landward end of the pier was
closed, and scheduled flights to and from New York City were
re-routed to Bader Field, Atlantic City's airport, said Robert
Shamberg, the manager on duty at Resorts International.
   The amusement pier, built in 1892, was destroyed by fire on Feb.
14, 1932, and rebuilt. It has been closed since 1986.
   Fires have plagued all the amusement piers built during the
city's heyday as a seaside resort around the turn of the century. In
1987, the Brigantine Castle Pier, a haunted amusement house, was
destroyed by fire.
   The Steel Pier, which is parallel to the Steeple Chase Pier, has
also been damaged by fires since its opening in 1898.
</TEXT>
