<FILEID>AP-NR-12-10-88 2331EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-QuakeAid 4thLd-Writethru   12-10 1217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Quake Aid, 4th Ld-Writethru,a0614,1200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Disaster Relief Experts, Rubble-Sniffing Dogs Fly to Soviet
Armenia</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Recasts lede and SUBS 7th graf, Members of..., to UPDATE with
relief plane arriving.
^By BRYAN BRUMLEY</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-six American disaster relief specialists
arrived Saturday in devastated Soviet Armenia with eight dogs
trained to sniff out survivors buried in the rubble of an earthquake
that killed tens of thousands of people.
   The flight was part of the biggest U.S. relief effort in the
Soviet Union since World War II. Americans provided limited
assistance after the partial meltdown of a nuclear reactor at
Chernobyl in the Soviet Ukraine in 1986.
   ``It's exciting, tough work, for which it is necessary to steel
yourself to devastation that boggles the mind,'' said Bill Dotson,
44, of Charlottesville, Va., head of the dog team that included a
golden retriever named Rubble.
   Dotson, a pharmaceutical biologist, said the rescue workers must
brace themselves for ``pieces of steel twisted like spaghetti'' by
the earthquake ``and the constant odor of death.''
   Dotson has been working with canine rescue teams for 15 years,
and helped search for survivors of the 1986 earthquake in El
Salvador. Other members of his team took part in relief efforts
stemming from the 1985 earthquake in Mexico City, mudslides in
Puerto Rico and Colombia and flooding in West Virginia.
   ``You get hooked on it. At first it is training the dog. Then it
is the challenge. And it is something that you can do to help other
people,'' Dotson said.
   Members of the American team left Dulles International Airport
outside Washington at 3:30 am. EST aboard a heavily loaded American
Trans Air 727. It arrived about 19 hours later at Yerevan, said
State Department spokeswoman Christine Murray.
   ``This is a special opportunity for us to reach out and work with
the Soviet Union,'' said Julia Taft, head of the Office of Foreign
Disaster Assistance of the State Department's Agency for
International Development.
   On a separate flight, 18 firefighters from Fairfax County, Va.,
and Miami left Saturday afternoon from Andrews Air Force Base
outside Washington. The firefighters were part of a special cave-in
response team that was enlisted Friday night by the State
Department. In addition to the fire fighters approximately 15-tons
of heavy equipment, food and supplies were aboard the Air Force C-5A.
   A chartered Boeing 707 carrying a 95,000-pound load of mostly
medical supplies and pharmaceuticals left John F. Kennedy
International Airport at mid-afternoon Saturday, also bound for
Yerevan. The flight was sponsored by Americares, based in New
Canaan, Conn.
   ``The American Red Cross is today sending 10,000 blood bags to
help victims of the Armenian earthquake. ... We'll also be sending
antibiotics, syringes and other medical supplies that have been
requested by the Soviet Red Cross,'' a statement said.
   Richard F. Schubert, President of the American Red Cross, said
this marks the first time that shipments of emergency supplies have
been accepted by the Soviet Red Cross.
   ``The tremendous outpouring of aid ... clearly demonstrates that
humanity transcends political and geographic frontiers,'' he said.
   At Los Angeles International Airport, workers loaded an
Occidental Petroleum Boeing 727 corporate jet with 2,300 pounds of
medical supplies mostly donated by the Red Cross. The jet was also
bringing $1 million contributed by Occidental and World Vision, a
privately funded international Christian relief agency.
   Occidental is chaired by Armand Hammer, who has long had ties
with the Soviet Union.
   Also accompanying the flight is Dr. Rosa Maria Durezo, 38, an
anesthesiologist on the UCLA medical staff who helped organize
relief medical services and supplies to Mexico City after the
September 1985 earthquake there.
   ``Our experience from the Mexican earthquake is that once the
damage is done, and it's three or four days later, there's not much
that can be done'' by doctors,'' she said. She said medical
treatment is mostly post-trauma treatment of people who have
suffered crushing injuries, infection and shock.
   In Boston, Oxfam America announced a $20,000 grant to provide
temporary shelters and medical supplies for the earthquake victims.
The International Association of Fire Chiefs said it was assembling
a 10-member rescue team to fly to the stricken area.
   President-elect Bush, accompanied by his wife, Barbara, and Brent
Scowcroft, his designated White House national security adviser,
visited the Soviet Embassy and signed a book of condolences for
earthquake victims.
   ``With anguish in our hearts for all those in the Soviet Union
who lost their loved ones,'' Bush wrote in the book.
   Soviet Ambassador Yuri Dubinin expressed gratitude for the
outpouring of aid and sympathy, while Bush said there should be a
free flow of relief efforts to the stricken area.
   ``If something has to be changed to expedite help to the people,
it should be done,'' Bush said. ``I know of no barriers.''
   The relief team that departed early Saturday included nine
doctors. Among them was Dr. Robert Gale of Los Angeles, who helped
treat radiation victims at Chernobyl.
   ``I have experience with disasters, experience with Soviet
disasters,'' Gale said. He said the political complications in
Armenia were less pronounced than at Chernobyl, where Soviet
authorities were criticized for maintaining secrecy after the
nuclear accident which carried radiation to neighboring countries.
   The other team members included Dr. Henry Sieligson, an emergency
room physician from Dekalb General Hospital in Atlanta, and Steve
McConaughy of Brookeville, Md., a canine team trainer who traveled
with his wife, Carol, and their black Newfoundland dogs, Ebony and
Shasta.
   The delegation also included Louise Simone, executive vice
president of the Armenian General Benevolent Union based in Saddle
Brook, N.J., and two doctors affiliated with the charitable society,
Garo Tertzakian and Vartkes Najarian, both of Los Angeles.
   ``For us, this is a long-term prospect to rebuild Armenia,'' said
Mrs. Simone, of New York City.
   She said the 80,000 people reported dead and 700,000 homeless
comprised about one-quarter of the 3.3 million people in Soviet
Armenia. Her foundation is raising millions of dollars to send
medicine and other relief supplies there.
   The dogs traveled with the human passengers in the main cabin,
which was packed with blankets, tents, hard hats and leather gloves
to protect the hands of workers who will try to pull victims from
the rubble of fallen buildings.
   Final arrangements for the flight were made during a meeting at
the State Department late Friday between Mrs. Taft and Yevgeny
Kutovoi, the No. 2 official at the Soviet Embassy, who said medical
supplies were urgently needed.
   Kutovoi said the Soviet government had established special bank
accounts for gifts. One account is at the Dupont Circle Branch of
the Riggs National Bank, 1913 Massachusetts Avenue N.W., Washington,
D.C. 20036. It was named the ``Earthquake Relief Fund,'' and its
number is 04-08-572-564.
   The Soviet Vnesheconbank in Moscow also has established a fund
for wire transfers, with the account number 70-000-412.
   The American Red Cross reported that money, antibiotics and kits
used to draw blood are being collected. The Soviet Embassy said it
was setting up a special telephone line to handle a deluge of calls
offering assistance.
   The American Red Cross has activated a toll-free number for
inquiries and offers of help. The number is 1-800-453-9000. The
public can make donations to local Red Cross chapters, designated
for Soviet Armenian Earthquake Relief, or through various Armenian
groups.
</TEXT>
