<1ST_LINE>u w AM-NuclearWeapons     12-10 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nuclear Weapons,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>DOE Recommends $50 Billion Reshuffling, Cleanup In Weapons Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Energy Department has recommended that the
United States spend $50 billion over the next two decades to
relocate two nuclear weapons material plants, build five new
production reactors and clean up environmental damage caused by bomb
production, the Washington Post reported in its Sunday's editions.
   Doug Elmets, the Energy Department spokesman, declined comment on
the story, but acknowledged that a classified report was being sent
to President Reagan to be taken to Capitol Hill on Thursday.
   The Post, quoting administration sources, said the Energy
Department recommends building four small reactors at the Idaho
National Engineering Laboratory near Idaho Falls instead of the
single unit the department proposed earlier this year. The
department also proposes a new, large reactor at the Savannah River
Plant in South Carolina.
   In the report, according to the paper, the department also
proposes closing a uranium foundry, the Feed Materials Production
Center, near Fernald, Ohio, and the Rocky Flats plutonium-processing
plant near Denver. It also recommends moving plutonium-related
activities out of the Pinellas Plant near Largo, Fla., and out of
the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory east of San Francisco
because, one of the newspaper's sources said, ``there are too many
people there.''
   The classified report, described by the Post as a blueprint for
the future of the nuclear-weapons complex, is scheduled to be
forwarded to the Senate and House Armed Services committees next
week, according to the paper. It said the report may be held up for
several weeks because of a dispute between the Energy Department and
the Office of Management and Budget over high costs.
</TEXT>
