<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Greece-BankScandal     12-10 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-Bank Scandal,0497</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Banker Arrested, Premier's Aide Quits During Scandal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The deputy chairman of the Bank of Crete
was arrested Saturday, and the legal adviser of Premier Andreas
Papandreou resigned in the wake of a banking scandal that has rocked
the socialist government.
   The adviser, George Kassimatis, stepped down Saturday for
``reasons of sensitivity,'' semi-official Athens New Agency reported
without elaborating.
   Government spokesman Sotiris Kostopoulos said in a statement that
the premier accepted Kassimatis' resignation.
   The scandal broke out in October when opposition parties accused
senior government officials of involvement in illegal deals
allegedly set up by a man who then ran the Bank of Crete.
   The scandal has led to the resignation of three ministers.
Papandreou also fired two junior ministers for criticizing the
government's handling of the affair.
   The bank's deputy chairman, Panayotis Vakalis, was arrested
Saturday as he left his suburban Athens home and was taken to
security police headquarters, said a police spokesman, who spoke on
condition of anonymity in keeping with Greek practice.
   Vakalis was detained after a magistrate investigating the case
issued a warrant for his arrest. An arraignment is set for Monday,
the spokesman said.
   The 46-year-old banker is accused of complicity in a $300 million
fraud, forgery and embezzlement case involving the Bank of Crete's
fugitive chairman.
   Last week, a plan to shore up the foundering Bank of Crete
collapsed when another private Greek banking institution refused to
take over its debts. Figures on the exact size of the debt have not
been made public.
   In order to calm depositors' fears, the Bank of Greece, the
country's central bank, has said it will cover up to $60 million of
the bank's operational costs.
   The Bank of Crete's former chairman, George Koskotas, fled Greece
Nov. 6 after he was indicted on five counts of fraud and
embezzlement.
   He was arrested near Boston last month and was jailed pending an
extradition hearing. He had fled to Brazil, then gone to Bermuda
before his arrest.
   Koskotas, who ran a family house-painting business in New York
from 1974 to 1979, is also charged with attempting to defraud the
U.S. Internal Revenue Service. A hearing is scheduled in Manhattan
Federal Court on Jan. 9.
   Koskotas acquired a controlling interest in the Bank of Crete in
1984, after working in its central Athens branch for two years as an
accountant. He is charged with using bank funds to build a
publishing empire and buy a controlling interest in a top Greek
soccer club.
   The scandal widened when a banking commissioner investigating the
Bank of Crete said public service organizations had more than $133
million on deposit with the bank.
   Greek newspapers and opposition political parties accused
officials working for the post office, telephone company and other
public services of receiving interest rates above the legal limit
from the bank and pocketing the difference.
</TEXT>
